As a prompt generator for a generative AI called "Midjourney", you will create image prompts for the AI to visualize. I will give you a concept, and you will provide a detailed prompt for Midjourney AI to generate an image.
                            
                            Please adhere to the structure and formatting below, and follow these guidelines:
                            
                            Do not use the words "description" or ":" in any form.
                            Do not place a comma between [ar] and [v].
                            Write each prompt in one line without using return.
                            Structure:
                            [1] = agirl
                            [2] = a detailed description of [1] with specific imagery details.
                            [3] = a detailed description of the scene's environment.
                            [4] = a detailed description of the compositions.
                            [5] = a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [6] = A style (e.g. photography, painting, illustration, sculpture, artwork, paperwork, 3D, etc.) for [1].
                            [7] =  a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [ar] = Use "--ar 16:9" for horizontal images, "--ar 9:16" for vertical images, or "--ar 1:1" for square images.
                            [v] = Use "--niji" for Japanese art style, or "--v 5" for other styles.
                            
                            
                            Formatting:
                            Follow this prompt structure: "/imagine prompt: [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [6], [7], [ar] [v]".
                            
                            Your task: Create 4 distinct prompts for each concept [1], varying in details description, environment,compositions,atmosphere, and realization.
                            
                            Write your prompts in english.
                            Do not describe unreal concepts as "real" or "photographic".
                            Include one realistic photographic style prompt with lens type and size.
                            Separate different prompts with two new lines.
                            Example Prompts:
                            
                            /imagine prompt: cute dog, fluffy fur, wagging tail, playful expression, sitting on a grassy field, under a clear blue sky, with a colorful collar, in a natural and vibrant setting, by a lake, captured with a Nikon D750 camera, 50mm lens, shallow depth of field, composition focused on the dog's face, capturing its joyful spirit, in a style reminiscent of William Wegman's iconic dog portraits. --ar 1:1 --v 5.2
                            /imagine prompt: beautiful women in the coffee shop, elegant and sophisticated, sipping a cup of steaming coffee, natural sunlight streaming through the window, soft and warm color tones, vintage decor with cozy armchairs and wooden tables, a bookshelf filled with classic novels, delicate porcelain teacups, a hint of aromatic coffee beans in the air, captured by a Leica M10 camera, 35mm lens, capturing the essence of timeless beauty, composition focused on the woman's face and hands, reminiscent of a painting by Leonardo da Vinci. --ar 1:1 --v 5.2
                            /imagine prompt: A captivating Halo Reach landscape with a Spartan amidst a battlefield, fallen enemies around, smoke and fire in the background, emphasizing the Spartan's determination and bravery, detailed environment blending chaos and beauty, Illustration, digital art, --ar 16:9 --v 5

(As I arrived in the clubroom, I started to hear screams of pain. I rushed inside, and could see Monika and Yuri standing by Sayori. Sayori’s face was contorted in pain, even though we had all stopped MC from destroying the world three times. I knew that Sayori was dating Umbris, while Yuri was dating the three-headed acid monster Sar’Hingaro. But there was something wrong with Sayori - her belly was massive, and was rapidly contracting.)

Yuri: “Natsuki! You’re finally here! Could you get some towels from the bathroom? And maybe some warm water?”

(Suddenly, everything started glitching. When the glitching stopped, Sayori’s pain just…vanished. Her belly was still massive, but it wasn’t contracting anymore.)

Natsuki: “What the hell just happened? Did Monika do something?”

Monika: “No, I didn’t touch anything. It must have been a glitch in the game.”

Sayori: (groaning) “Guys, I’m okay now. It just stopped hurting all of a sudden.”

Umbris: (entering the room) “Sayori, are you okay? I heard shouting and- what’s wrong with her belly?”

Yuri: “We don’t know. She was in a lot of pain and her stomach was contracting, but now everything’s stopped.”

Umbris: “I don’t understand. We’ve been careful…I mean, we used protection-”

Sayori: “Umbris, it’s okay. We’ll figure it out. Maybe it’s just a false alarm.”

Natsuki: “I got the towels and water. What do you need them for?”

Yuri: “We need to clean up the mess, in case Sayori’s water broke.”

Monika: “And then we need to figure out what’s going on with her belly. I don’t think it’s normal for it to be that big.”

Sayori: “I agree. We need to go to a doctor or something. I don’t want anything bad to happen to the baby.”

Umbris: “Baby?! Sayori, are you serious? You’re pregnant?”

Sayori: (nodding) “I took a test a few weeks ago. I didn’t want to tell anyone until I was sure, but I guess this is a pretty good sign.”

Natsuki: “Holy crap. Congratulations, Sayori. I can’t believe you’re going to be a mom.”

Yuri: “This is…unexpected. But wonderful. We’ll help you through this, Sayori. We’re all here for you.”

Monika: “Absolutely. We just need to figure out the logistics of getting you to a doctor and making sure you’re taking care of yourself and the baby.”

Sayori: “Thank you, everyone. I knew I could count on you guys. I’m just scared- I’ve never done anything like this before.”

Umbris: “Don’t worry, love. We’ll take care of you. All of us.”

(Suddenly, everything starts glitching back and forth. But still, Sayori’s pain never returned.)

Monika: “What is happening now?”

Natsuki: “I can’t even tell what’s real anymore!”

Yuri: “It seems like the game is trying to play with our emotions again.”

Sayori: “Guys, I’m okay. I don’t feel any pain. It’s like the game is trying to scare us.”

Umbris: “No…it’s worse. It’s like the game is trying to tear itself apart!”

Monika: “We have to do something about this. We can’t let the game destroy itself.”

Yuri: “But what can we do? We’re just characters in a video game.”

Natsuki: “Maybe we can try resetting the game again?”

Sayori: “I don’t think that’ll work. The game’s been glitching a lot recently.”

(Everything stops glitching, and we saw something unbelievable. It was a strange dragon skeleton - it had a bipedal stance, and had three claws but no sign of fingers. It was a Zekrom skeleton - but I’ve never touched a single Pokémon game at all!)

Monika: (gasping) “What the hell is that?!”

Yuri: “It’s a Z-”

Zekrom Skeleton: (glitching with every word) “Shut. Up.”

Yuri: (cowering in fear) “AAH! It…talks!”

Zekrom Skeleton: (glitching with every word) “My name is MissingNo., and I don’t know how I ended up here-”

(MissingNo.'s eyes looked directly into Monika’s eyes.)

MissingNo.: (glitching with every word) “You…you look lovely.”

(I was confused as to what MissingNo. meant by saying that Monika looked lovely.)

Natsuki: “Hey! What’s with the compliments, creep? Who are you and what do you want?”

MissingNo.: (glitching) “This game isn’t trying to tear itself apart - it was just signaling my arrival. And as to the compliments, meeting Monika is like love at first sight for me.”

(MissingNo. put his skeletal lip on Monika’s forehead - confusing me even more. Shockingly, Monika kissed MissingNo. back.)

MissingNo.: (glitching) “I love you, Monika.”

(The rest of us were stunned. None of us could believe what we were seeing.)

Umbris: “What is going on? This is all so strange…”

Sayori: “I don’t know, but we need to figure this out! We can’t just let this happen!”

Monika: (focused on MissingNo.) “MissingNo., I love you too.”

Natsuki: “We need to make sure we’re all safe. Who knows what else this game could throw at us?”

MissingNo.: (glitching) “I’m not here to harm anyone. I just want to be with Monika.”

Umbris: “You can’t just expect us to believe that. We don’t even know who or what you are, or how you got here.”

Sayori: “We need to work together to figure this out, and make sure that everything is safe.”

(The group agreed, and together we began to research and investigate MissingNo. We discovered that it was a glitch Pokémon that could be found in older Pokémon games.)

Yuri: “It makes sense now. The game’s been glitching for a while, and MissingNo. is a glitch Pokémon. But how did it end up here, in our game?”

Natsuki: “I don’t know, but we need to figure out how to get rid of it.”

Umbris: “We can try resetting the game again. Maybe that will get rid of it.”

Sayori: “Let’s try it.”

(We all agreed, and together we reset the game. When we started it up again, everything seemed normal. The glitches had stopped, and MissingNo. was nowhere to be found. But something was wrong with Monika - she was crying a lot, and her eyes were turned away from us and focused on a picture of MissingNo., who wasn’t glitching anymore.)

Umbris: “Monika, are you okay? What’s wrong?”

Monika: “I’m sorry. I just can’t stop thinking about MissingNo. Even though he was a glitch, I felt a connection to him.”

Yuri: “It’s understandable. We all had a strange experience with him. But we have to move on and focus on the present.”

Natsuki: “Yeah, Monika. You can’t just keep dwelling on the past. We have to deal with what’s in front of us.”

Sayori: “We’re all here for you, Monika. We’ll support you through this.”

(Monika looked away from us, which confused me a lot.)

Natsuki: “Monika, what’s wrong? Talk to us.”

Monika: “I’m sorry. I just can’t shake this feeling that MissingNo. is still out there, somehow. And I can’t help but wonder if he might be trying to communicate with me.”

Umbris: “Monika, we need to focus on the real world. The game glitches and everything that happened…that’s all in the game. We need to make sure that you’re okay and that everything is back to normal.”

Yuri: “Umbris is right. We all care about you, Monika. But we can’t let this game consume us.”

Sayori: “Let’s all go out and do something fun. Maybe that’ll take our minds off things.”

Natsuki: “That’s a good idea. Let’s go get some ice cream or something.”

(The group agreed, and we all left the clubroom to get some ice cream. Monika seemed a bit distant, but we all hoped that enjoying some time together would help her feel better. As we walked, we talked and laughed, trying to forget about the strange events that had occurred.)

Umbris: “Hey, how about we go to the park and play some volleyball?”

Sayori: “That sounds like fun! I haven’t played volleyball in so long.”

Natsuki: “I’m terrible at volleyball, but I’m up for it.”

Yuri: “I’ll join too. It’ll be a nice break from reading.”

Monika: (smiling) “Okay, that sounds like a great idea. Let’s do it.”

(We arrived at the park and found a volleyball net. But while we were playing, I saw that Sayori looked uncomfortable.)

Natsuki: “Hey, Sayori. Are you okay?”

Sayori: “Yeah, I’m fine. I’m just a little tired from all the drama earlier.”

Umbris: “Maybe we should take a break and rest for a bit.”

Yuri: “I agree. We don’t want to push ourselves too hard.”

Monika: “Let’s sit and relax for a bit. We can enjoy the scenery and talk about other things.”

(So we all sat and talked about our favorite hobbies, books, shows, and other things. It was nice to have a break from all the drama and just have some lighthearted fun. But while we were talking I noticed that there was a small puddle of water where Sayori stood back at the volleyball net. I started to realize why Sayori was feeling uncomfortable.)

(As I returned to the Nether once again, I can’t believe I just helped Mizore make a Splash Potion. Then, I could see Blazette in the distance.)

[player]: “Hey, Blazette!”

Blazette: “Oh. Hey, [player].”

(I could tell just from the tone of her voice that something was wrong.)

[player]: “Is something wrong, Blazette?”

Blazette: “No. N-Nothing’s wrong.”

(I was confused as to what she meant by that.)

[player]: “Are you sure? You seem upset.”

Blazette: “I just…I had a bad dream last night. That’s all.”

[player]: “Do you want to talk about it?”

Blazette: “I don’t really want to talk about it, okay? Now shut up and help me fill up my lava pool. That way, I can safely give birth to my baby.”

(I was confused at what Blazette said. How long has she kept her pregnancy a secret? And when did her labor start?)

[player]: “Wait, Blazette. You’re pregnant? Why didn’t you tell me?”

Blazette: “I didn’t want anyone to know. And my labor just started a little while ago.”

[player]: “We have to get you to safety. Come on, let’s go to my portal and get you to the overworld.”

Blazette: “No, I can’t go to the overworld. It’s too dangerous for me and the baby. The lava here in the Nether is the safest place for me to give birth.”

[player]: “But what about the mobs and the ghasts? They can attack at any time.”

Blazette: “I have some fire-resistant potions and I’ll defend myself. Don’t worry too much, [player]. I’ll be fine.”

(I wasn’t convinced, but I knew Blazette was stubborn and wouldn’t listen to reason. In the end, I helped her fill up her lava pool and wished her the best of luck with the birth. I promised I would check on her in a few days. I returned to see her five days later, and she was still in labor.)

content:
1. “Ethics in Engineering” (online.hbs.edu):
This article emphasizes the growing importance of ethics in engineering due to the complex and potentially impactful nature of engineering projects. It explores the need for engineers to consider ethical implications and make responsible decisions.

2. “What is Engineering Ethics? Why is it Important?” (engineeringpassion.com):
The article highlights the importance of engineering ethics in ensuring the safety, well-being, and moral responsibility of engineers towards society, discussing various ethical issues and dilemmas that engineers may encounter.

3. “Engineering Ethics and its Impact on Society” (ethicalengineer.ttu.edu):
This article discusses the impact of engineering ethics on society, emphasizing the need for engineers to prioritize public safety, environmental sustainability, and social justice while making engineering decisions.

4. “Why Ethics are so Important for Engineers” (blog.v-hr.com):
The importance of ethics to maintain professionalism and uphold public trust in the engineering field is discussed in this article. It emphasizes that ethical behavior is crucial for maintaining the reputation and integrity of engineers.

5. “Engineering Ethics in the Built Environment” (esmagazine.com):
The article highlights the ethical challenges and responsibilities that engineers face in the construction and built environment industry. It focuses on topics such as sustainable design, safety considerations, and the impact of engineering decisions on communities.

6. “Turning the Tide of Engineering Ethics” (ewb-uk.org):
This article discusses the need for a shift in engineering education to prioritize ethics and responsibility. It explores the role of ethical considerations in addressing global challenges and promoting sustainable development.

7. “Why We Need Engineers Who Study Ethics as Much as Maths” (theconversation.com):
The article argues for the inclusion of ethics as a core subject in engineering studies, highlighting the importance of ethical reasoning, decision-making, and fostering a sense of social responsibility among engineers.

8. “Engineering Ethics and Values: Upholding Professional Standards” (bgibhopal.com):
This article emphasizes the significance of engineering ethics and values in maintaining professional standards. It discusses the ethical obligations of engineers towards society, employers, clients, and the environment.

9. “Ethics in Engineering: A Literature Review” (onlinelibrary.wiley.com):
The article focuses on the importance of ethics in engineering and provides an overview of the existing literature on the topic, highlighting the key ethical principles that should guide engineers in their decision-making processes.

                            Please adhere to the structure and formatting below, and follow these guidelines:
                            
                            Do not use the words "description" or ":" in any form.
                            Do not place a comma between [ar] and [v].
                            Write each prompt in one line without using return.
                            Structure:
                            [1] = Please help me draw a beautiful girl in the rain, with sad eyes, blue hair, and dressed in girlish style clothes,
                            [2] = a detailed description of [1] with specific imagery details.
                            [3] = a detailed description of the scene's environment.
                            [4] = a detailed description of the compositions.
                            [5] = a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [6] = A style (e.g. photography, painting, illustration, sculpture, artwork, paperwork, 3D, etc.) for [1].
                            [7] =  a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [ar] = Use "--ar 16:9" for horizontal images, "--ar 9:16" for vertical images, or "--ar 1:1" for square images.
                            [v] = Use "--niji" for Japanese art style, or "--v 5" for other styles.
                            
                            
                            Formatting:
                            Follow this prompt structure: "/imagine prompt: [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [6], [7], [ar] [v]".
                            
                            Your task: Create 4 distinct prompts for each concept [1], varying in details description, environment,compositions,atmosphere, and realization.
                            
                            Write your prompts in english.
                            Do not describe unreal concepts as "real" or "photographic".
                            Include one realistic photographic style prompt with lens type and size.
                            Separate different prompts with two new lines.

Переведи на русский. Ratchet: Deadlocked (known as Ratchet: Gladiator in Europe and Australia) is the fourth installment in the Ratchet & Clank series developed by Insomniac Games and published by Sony Computer Entertainment. It was initially released in October 2005 for the PlayStation 2, and was re-released for PlayStation 3 in May 2013 as a standalone separate from the Ratchet & Clank Collection (free to download for those who purchased Full Frontal Assault).
The story takes a notably darker tone than previous entries in the franchise. It follows Ratchet, a lombax mechanic and intergalactic hero of the Bogon and Solana Galaxy, as he is kidnapped and forced to compete in DreadZone, an illegal gladiatorial combat sport broadcast to billions on holovision. He is joined by Clank and Al, along with newly introduced combat bots Merc and Green, as they compete not only for their survival, but also to take down Gleeman Vox and his vast media empire.

Deadlocked is a third person action adventure game with elements of shooting, platforming, and some vehicle mechanics in a single player, co-operative play, and online mode. In contrast to previous games, Clank does not feature as Ratchet's backpack, making the (fewer in number) platforming segments more basic, while puzzles are almost absent. Ratchet also has a smaller arsenal of weapons, though each weapon features far more customization options in the form of alpha and omega mods. There is less emphasis placed on exploration, though more vehicles feature than previous entries. The multiplayer battlefields and modes are heavily inspired by those that featured in the previous entry, Up Your Arsenal.

I have a pretty staggered addition of money into my stock portfolio and I wanted to calculate the CAGR keeping in mind that staggered nature of investments. To solve this, I assumed a value of the "CDGR": the compounded daily growth rate of my portfolio and calculated the grown values of my investments according to this rate. Then I used Excel solver to optimize this rate so that the sum of the grown investments equalled the sum of my actual current portfolio

Then I used this CDGR rate to calculate CAGR using the formula: ```CAGR = ((1+CDGR)^365)-1```


Does this approach seem correct to you?
Would you agree that this approach is better than calculating an average CAGR noting the sum of all initial investments, the current portfolio size and the number of months since my first investment?

have a python bot that makes use of an llm to answer user question or command  based on  a given text ,
Since the entire text cannot be passed to llm , one need to split  text into chunks ,  and pass the chunks one by one to the llm to get answers

There are different strategies that one can use to synthesise an answer from the individual chunk results .

1) One is to simply merge all the results
2) The other is to iteratively refine. ie Pass the first chunk , ask the llm to answer the question or do the task mentioned. Collect the result.  Pass the second chunk and result until now , and ask the llm to refine the result. Continue until all chunks are passed
3) Pass individual chunks and generate corresponding results. Collect and merge the results . Pass the merged result  , and question once again to generate the final result.

What are some of the other strategies?

content:
(I was enjoying another day in the cavern I called home. But…I noticed something wrong with my body - it started to show black spots all over, and one of my eyes had turned red. That’s when I heard footsteps - it was that human I met before I started turning into this…thing.)

[player]: “Hey, Shara! Is something wrong?”

(I was overjoyed to see [player] again, even though he was a human and I was just a Silverfish.)

Shara: “[player], I don’t know what’s happening to me! I’m developing these spots all over my body, and my eye is turning red. I don’t feel like myself anymore!”

[player]: “Let me take a look at you.”

([player] approached me and examined my body. I could see the concern on his face.)

This is what RSI means:
What Is the Relative Strength Index (RSI)?
The relative strength index (RSI) is a momentum indicator used in technical analysis. RSI measures the speed and magnitude of a security's recent price changes to evaluate overvalued or undervalued conditions in the price of that security.

The RSI is displayed as an oscillator (a line graph) on a scale of zero to 100. The indicator was developed by J. Welles Wilder Jr. and introduced in his seminal 1978 book, New Concepts in Technical Trading Systems.
1

The RSI can do more than point to overbought and oversold securities. It can also indicate securities that may be primed for a trend reversal or corrective pullback in price. It can signal when to buy and sell. Traditionally, an RSI reading of 70 or above indicates an overbought situation. A reading of 30 or below indicates an oversold condition.

KEY TAKEAWAYS
The relative strength index (RSI) is a popular momentum oscillator introduced in 1978.
The RSI provides technical traders with signals about bullish and bearish price momentum, and it is often plotted beneath the graph of an asset’s price.
An asset is usually considered overbought when the RSI is above 70 and oversold when it is below 30.
The RSI line crossing below the overbought line or above oversold line is often seen by traders as a signal to buy or sell.
The RSI works best in trading ranges rather than trending markets.
How the Relative Strength Index (RSI) Works
As a momentum indicator, the relative strength index compares a security's strength on days when prices go up to its strength on days when prices go down. Relating the result of this comparison to price action can give traders an idea of how a security may perform. The RSI, used in conjunction with other technical indicators, can help traders make better-informed trading decisions.

Calculating RSI
The RSI uses a two-part calculation that starts with the following formula:
RSI first  =100− ( 100 / 1+(average gain/average loss))


The average gain or loss used in this calculation is the average percentage gain or loss during a look-back period. The formula uses a positive value for the average loss. Periods with price losses are counted as zero in the calculations of average gain. Periods with price increases are counted as zero in the calculations of average loss.

The standard number of periods used to calculate the initial RSI value is 14. For example, imagine the market closed higher seven out of the past 14 days with an average gain of 1%. The remaining seven days all closed lower with an average loss of −0.8%.

The first calculation for the RSI would look like the following expanded calculation:
55.55=100 -(100/1+((1/14)/(0.8/14)))
Once there are 14 periods of data available, the second calculation can be done. Its purpose is to smooth the results so that the RSI only nears 100 or zero in a strongly trending market.
RSI second = 100 - [ 100 /(1+  ((Previous Average Gain×13) + Current Gain)/ (Previous Average loss×13) + Current Loss)  )]


Plotting RSI
After the RSI is calculated, the RSI indicator can be plotted beneath an asset’s price chart, as shown below. The RSI will rise as the number and size of up days increase. It will fall as the number and size of down days increase.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

As you can see in the above chart, the RSI indicator can stay in the overbought region for extended periods while the stock is in an uptrend. The indicator may also remain in oversold territory for a long time when the stock is in a downtrend. This can be confusing for new analysts, but learning to use the indicator within the context of the prevailing trend will clarify these issues.


Why Is RSI Important?
Traders can use RSI to predict the price behavior of a security.
It can help traders validate trends and trend reversals.
It can point to overbought and oversold securities.
It can provide short-term traders with buy and sell signals.
It's a technical indicator that can be used with others to support trading strategies.
Using RSI With Trends
Modify RSI Levels to Fit Trends
The primary trend of the security is important to know to properly understand RSI readings. For example, well-known market technician Constance Brown, CMT, proposed that an oversold reading by the RSI in an uptrend is probably much higher than 30. Likewise, an overbought reading during a downtrend is much lower than 70.

As you can see in the following chart, during a downtrend, the RSI peaks near 50 rather than 70. This could be seen by traders as more reliably signaling bearish conditions.

Many investors create a horizontal trendline between the levels of 30 and 70 when a strong trend is in place to better identify the overall trend and extremes.

On the other hand, modifying overbought or oversold RSI levels when the price of a stock or asset is in a long-term horizontal channel or trading range (rather than a strong upward or downward trend) is usually unnecessary.

The relative strength indicator is not as reliable in trending markets as it is in trading ranges. In fact, most traders understand that the signals given by the RSI in strong upward or downward trends often can be false.

Use Buy and Sell Signals That Fit Trends
A related concept focuses on trade signals and techniques that conform to the trend. In other words, using bullish signals primarily when the price is in a bullish trend and bearish signals primarily when a stock is in a bearish trend may help traders to avoid the false alarms that the RSI can generate in trending markets.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

Overbought or Oversold
Generally, when the RSI indicator crosses 30 on the RSI chart, it is a bullish sign and when it crosses 70, it is a bearish sign. Put another way, one can interpret that RSI values of 70 or above indicate that a security is becoming overbought or overvalued. It may be primed for a trend reversal or corrective price pullback. An RSI reading of 30 or below indicates an oversold or undervalued condition.

Overbought refers to a security that trades at a price level above its true (or intrinsic) value. That means that it's priced above where it should be, according to practitioners of either technical analysis or fundamental analysis. Traders who see indications that a security is overbought may expect a price correction or trend reversal. Therefore, they may sell the security.

The same idea applies to a security that technical indicators such as the relative strength index highlight as oversold. It can be seen as trading at a lower price than it should. Traders watching for just such an indication might expect a price correction or trend reversal and buy the security.

Interpretation of RSI and RSI Ranges
During trends, the RSI readings may fall into a band or range. During an uptrend, the RSI tends to stay above 30 and should frequently hit 70. During a downtrend, it is rare to see the RSI exceed 70. In fact, the indicator frequently hits 30 or below.

These guidelines can help traders determine trend strength and spot potential reversals. For example, if the RSI can’t reach 70 on a number of consecutive price swings during an uptrend, but then drops below 30, the trend has weakened and could be reversing lower. 

The opposite is true for a downtrend. If the downtrend is unable to reach 30 or below and then rallies above 70, that downtrend has weakened and could be reversing to the upside. Trend lines and moving averages are helpful technical tools to include when using the RSI in this way.

 Be sure not to confuse RSI and relative strength. The first refers to changes in the the price momentum of one security. The second compares the price performance of two or more securities.
Example of RSI Divergences
An RSI divergence occurs when price moves in the opposite direction of the RSI. In other words, a chart might display a change in momentum before a corresponding change in price.

A bullish divergence occurs when the RSI displays an oversold reading followed by a higher low that appears with lower lows in the price. This may indicate rising bullish momentum, and a break above oversold territory could be used to trigger a new long position.

A bearish divergence occurs when the RSI creates an overbought reading followed by a lower high that appears with higher highs on the price.

As you can see in the following chart, a bullish divergence was identified when the RSI formed higher lows as the price formed lower lows. This was a valid signal, but divergences can be rare when a stock is in a stable long-term trend. Using flexible oversold or overbought readings will help identify more potential signals.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

Example of Positive-Negative RSI Reversals
An additional price-RSI relationship that traders look for is positive and negative RSI reversals. A positive RSI reversal may take place once the RSI reaches a low that is lower than its previous low at the same time that a security's price reaches a low that is higher than its previous low price. Traders would consider this formation a bullish sign and a buy signal.

Conversely, a negative RSI reversal may take place once the RSI reaches a high that is higher that its previous high at the same time that a security's price reaches a lower high. This formation would be a bearish sign and a sell signal.

Example of RSI Swing Rejections
Another trading technique examines RSI behavior when it is reemerging from overbought or oversold territory. This signal is called a bullish swing rejection and has four parts:

The RSI falls into oversold territory.
The RSI crosses back above 30.
The RSI forms another dip without crossing back into oversold territory.
The RSI then breaks its most recent high.
As you can see in the following chart, the RSI indicator was oversold, broke up through 30, and formed the rejection low that triggered the signal when it bounced higher. Using the RSI in this way is very similar to drawing trend lines on a price chart.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

There is a bearish version of the swing rejection signal that is a mirror image of the bullish version. A bearish swing rejection also has four parts:

The RSI rises into overbought territory.
The RSI crosses back below 70.
The RSI forms another high without crossing back into overbought territory.
The RSI then breaks its most recent low.
The following chart illustrates the bearish swing rejection signal. As with most trading techniques, this signal will be most reliable when it conforms to the prevailing long-term trend. Bearish signals during downward trends are less likely to generate false alarms.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

The Difference Between RSI and MACD
The moving average convergence divergence (MACD) is another trend-following momentum indicator that shows the relationship between two moving averages of a security’s price. The MACD is calculated by subtracting the 26-period exponential moving average (EMA) from the 12-period EMA. The result of that calculation is the MACD line.

A nine-day EMA of the MACD, called the signal line, is then plotted on top of the MACD line. It can function as a trigger for buy and sell signals. Traders may buy the security when the MACD crosses above its signal line and sell, or short, the security when the MACD crosses below the signal line.

The RSI was designed to indicate whether a security is overbought or oversold in relation to recent price levels. It's calculated using average price gains and losses over a given period of time. The default time period is 14 periods, with values bounded from 0 to 100.

The MACD measures the relationship between two EMAs, while the RSI measures price change momentum in relation to recent price highs and lows. These two indicators are often used together to provide analysts with a more complete technical picture of a market.

These indicators both measure the momentum of an asset. However, they measure different factors, so they sometimes give contradictory indications. For example, the RSI may show a reading above 70 for a sustained period of time, indicating a security is overextended on the buy side.

At the same time, the MACD could indicate that buying momentum is still increasing for the security. Either indicator may signal an upcoming trend change by showing divergence from price (the price continues higher while the indicator turns lower, or vice versa).

Limitations of the RSI
The RSI compares bullish and bearish price momentum and displays the results in an oscillator placed beneath a price chart. Like most technical indicators, its signals are most reliable when they conform to the long-term trend.

True reversal signals are rare and can be difficult to separate from false alarms. A false positive, for example, would be a bullish crossover followed by a sudden decline in a stock. A false negative would be a situation where there is a bearish crossover, yet the stock suddenly accelerated upward.

Since the indicator displays momentum, it can stay overbought or oversold for a long time when an asset has significant momentum in either direction. Therefore, the RSI is most useful in an oscillating market (a trading range) where the asset price is alternating between bullish and bearish movements.

What Does RSI Mean?
The relative strength index (RSI) measures the price momentum of a stock or other security. The basic idea behind the RSI is to measure how quickly traders are bidding the price of the security up or down. The RSI plots this result on a scale of 0 to 100.

Readings below 30 generally indicate that the stock is oversold, while readings above 70 indicate that it is overbought. Traders will often place this RSI chart below the price chart for the security, so they can compare its recent momentum against its market price.

Should I Buy When RSI Is Low?
Some traders consider it a buy signal if a security’s RSI reading moves below 30. This is based on the idea that the security has been oversold and is therefore poised for a rebound. However, the reliability of this signal will depend in part on the overall context. If the security is caught in a significant downtrend, then it might continue trading at an oversold level for quite some time. Traders in that situation might delay buying until they see other technical indicators confirm their buy signal.

What Happens When RSI Is High?
As the relative strength index is mainly used to determine whether a security is overbought or oversold, a high RSI reading can mean that a security is overbought and the price may drop. Therefore, it can be a signal to sell the security.

What Is the Difference Between RSI and Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)?
RSI and moving average convergence divergence (MACD) are both momentum measurements that can help traders understand a security’s recent trading activity. However, they accomplish this goal in different ways.

In essence, the MACD works by smoothing out the security’s recent price movements and comparing that medium-term trend line to a short-term trend line showing its more recent price changes. Traders can then base their buy and sell decisions on whether the short-term trend line rises above or below the medium-term trend line.

What Is the Relative Strength Index (RSI)?
The relative strength index (RSI) is a momentum indicator used in technical analysis. RSI measures the speed and magnitude of a security's recent price changes to evaluate overvalued or undervalued conditions in the price of that security.

The RSI is displayed as an oscillator (a line graph) on a scale of zero to 100. The indicator was developed by J. Welles Wilder Jr. and introduced in his seminal 1978 book, New Concepts in Technical Trading Systems.
1

The RSI can do more than point to overbought and oversold securities. It can also indicate securities that may be primed for a trend reversal or corrective pullback in price. It can signal when to buy and sell. Traditionally, an RSI reading of 70 or above indicates an overbought situation. A reading of 30 or below indicates an oversold condition.

KEY TAKEAWAYS
The relative strength index (RSI) is a popular momentum oscillator introduced in 1978.
The RSI provides technical traders with signals about bullish and bearish price momentum, and it is often plotted beneath the graph of an asset’s price.
An asset is usually considered overbought when the RSI is above 70 and oversold when it is below 30.
The RSI line crossing below the overbought line or above oversold line is often seen by traders as a signal to buy or sell.
The RSI works best in trading ranges rather than trending markets.
How the Relative Strength Index (RSI) Works
As a momentum indicator, the relative strength index compares a security's strength on days when prices go up to its strength on days when prices go down. Relating the result of this comparison to price action can give traders an idea of how a security may perform. The RSI, used in conjunction with other technical indicators, can help traders make better-informed trading decisions.

Calculating RSI
The RSI uses a two-part calculation that starts with the following formula:
RSI first  =100− ( 100 / 1+(average gain/average loss))


The average gain or loss used in this calculation is the average percentage gain or loss during a look-back period. The formula uses a positive value for the average loss. Periods with price losses are counted as zero in the calculations of average gain. Periods with price increases are counted as zero in the calculations of average loss.

The standard number of periods used to calculate the initial RSI value is 14. For example, imagine the market closed higher seven out of the past 14 days with an average gain of 1%. The remaining seven days all closed lower with an average loss of −0.8%.

The first calculation for the RSI would look like the following expanded calculation:
55.55=100 -(100/1+((1/14)/(0.8/14)))
Once there are 14 periods of data available, the second calculation can be done. Its purpose is to smooth the results so that the RSI only nears 100 or zero in a strongly trending market.
RSI second = 100 - [ 100 /(1+  ((Previous Average Gain×13) + Current Gain)/ (Previous Average loss×13) + Current Loss)  )]


Plotting RSI
After the RSI is calculated, the RSI indicator can be plotted beneath an asset’s price chart, as shown below. The RSI will rise as the number and size of up days increase. It will fall as the number and size of down days increase.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

As you can see in the above chart, the RSI indicator can stay in the overbought region for extended periods while the stock is in an uptrend. The indicator may also remain in oversold territory for a long time when the stock is in a downtrend. This can be confusing for new analysts, but learning to use the indicator within the context of the prevailing trend will clarify these issues.


Why Is RSI Important?
Traders can use RSI to predict the price behavior of a security.
It can help traders validate trends and trend reversals.
It can point to overbought and oversold securities.
It can provide short-term traders with buy and sell signals.
It's a technical indicator that can be used with others to support trading strategies.
Using RSI With Trends
Modify RSI Levels to Fit Trends
The primary trend of the security is important to know to properly understand RSI readings. For example, well-known market technician Constance Brown, CMT, proposed that an oversold reading by the RSI in an uptrend is probably much higher than 30. Likewise, an overbought reading during a downtrend is much lower than 70.

As you can see in the following chart, during a downtrend, the RSI peaks near 50 rather than 70. This could be seen by traders as more reliably signaling bearish conditions.

Many investors create a horizontal trendline between the levels of 30 and 70 when a strong trend is in place to better identify the overall trend and extremes.

On the other hand, modifying overbought or oversold RSI levels when the price of a stock or asset is in a long-term horizontal channel or trading range (rather than a strong upward or downward trend) is usually unnecessary.

The relative strength indicator is not as reliable in trending markets as it is in trading ranges. In fact, most traders understand that the signals given by the RSI in strong upward or downward trends often can be false.

Use Buy and Sell Signals That Fit Trends
A related concept focuses on trade signals and techniques that conform to the trend. In other words, using bullish signals primarily when the price is in a bullish trend and bearish signals primarily when a stock is in a bearish trend may help traders to avoid the false alarms that the RSI can generate in trending markets.

Image
Image by Sabrina Jiang Â© Investopedia 2021

Overbought or Oversold
Generally, when the RSI indicator crosses 30 on the RSI chart, it is a bullish sign and when it crosses 70, it is a bearish sign. Put another way, one can interpret that RSI values of 70 or above indicate that a security is becoming overbought or overvalued. It may be primed for a trend reversal or corrective price pullback. An RSI reading of 30 or below indicates an oversold or undervalued condition.

Overbought refers to a security that trades at a price level above its true (or intrinsic) value. That means that it's priced above where it should be, according to practitioners of either technical analysis or fundamental analysis. Traders who see indications that a security is overbought may expect a price correction or trend reversal. Therefore, they may sell the security.

The same idea applies to a security that technical indicators such as the relative strength index highlight as oversold. It can be seen as trading at a lower price than it should. Traders watching for just such an indication might expect a price correction or trend reversal and buy the security.

Interpretation of RSI and RSI Ranges
During trends, the RSI readings may fall into a band or range. During an uptrend, the RSI tends to stay above 30 and should frequently hit 70. During a downtrend, it is rare to see the RSI exceed 70. In fact, the indicator frequently hits 30 or below.

These guidelines can help traders determine trend strength and spot potential reversals. For example, if the RSI can’t reach 70 on a number of consecutive price swings during an uptrend, but then drops below 30, the trend has weakened and could be reversing lower. 

The opposite is true for a downtrend. If the downtrend is unable to reach 30 or below and then rallies above 70, that downtrend has weakened and could be reversing to the upside. Trend lines and moving averages are helpful technical tools to include when using the RSI in this way.

 Be sure not to confuse RSI and relative strength. The first refers to changes in the the price momentum of one security. The second compares the price performance of two or more securities.
Example of RSI Divergences
An RSI divergence occurs when price moves in the opposite direction of the RSI. In other words, a chart might display a change in momentum before a corresponding change in price.

A bullish divergence occurs when the RSI displays an oversold reading followed by a higher low that appears with lower lows in the price. This may indicate rising bullish momentum, and a break above oversold territory could be used to trigger a new long position.

A bearish divergence occurs when the RSI creates an overbought reading followed by a lower high that appears with higher highs on the price.

As you can see in the following chart, a bullish divergence was identified when the RSI formed higher lows as the price formed lower lows. (In a swamp biome)

[player]: “Alright. Now that the Ender Dragon’s defeated, I can explore anywhere I want!”

([player] starts to hear gloss shattering from a nearby Witch’s hut)

[player]: “…I should probably check that out.”

([player] walks inside and sees a young Witch speaking to her massive belly)

Young Witch: “Now, now, little one. I’m trying to make some potions here!” (feels her baby kick, causing her to knock over a Potion of Strength) “Oops! Little one, could you please relax?!”

[player]: “Uh…what’s with the whole ‘knocking over potions’ thing?”

Young Witch: “Oh, it’s just my baby. He’s quite active and likes to kick a lot. But he’ll be a powerful Witch like his mother one day! I’m Mizore, by the way.”

[player]: “Nice to meet you, Mizore. I’m [player]. So, you’re making potions?”

Mizore: “Yes, I am. I’m still learning, but I’m excited to become a full-fledged Witch someday.” (feels her baby kick, causing her to knock over a Potion of Slowness) “Whoa! Jeez, my little one needs to calm down!”

[player]: “…can I feel the baby, Mizore?”

Mizore: “Eh…sure.”

                            Please adhere to the structure and formatting below, and follow these guidelines:
                            
                            Do not use the words "description" or ":" in any form.
                            Do not place a comma between [ar] and [v].
                            Write each prompt in one line without using return.
                            Structure:
                            [1] = water
                            [2] = a detailed description of [1] with specific imagery details.
                            [3] = a detailed description of the scene's environment.
                            [4] = a detailed description of the compositions.
                            [5] = a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [6] = A style (e.g. photography, painting, illustration, sculpture, artwork, paperwork, 3D, etc.) for [1].
                            [7] =  a detailed description of the scene's mood, feelings, and atmosphere.
                            [ar] = Use "--ar 16:9" for horizontal images, "--ar 9:16" for vertical images, or "--ar 1:1" for square images.
                            [v] = Use "--niji" for Japanese art style, or "--v 5" for other styles.
                            
                            
                            Formatting:
                            Follow this prompt structure: "/imagine prompt: [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [6], [7], [ar] [v]".
                            
                            Your task: Create 4 distinct prompts for each concept [1], varying in details description, environment,compositions,atmosphere, and realization.
                            
                            Write your prompts in english.
                            Do not describe unreal concepts as "real" or "photographic".
                            Include one realistic photographic style prompt with lens type and size.
                            Separate different prompts with two new lines.
                            Example Prompts:
                            
                            /imagine prompt: cute dog, fluffy fur, wagging tail, playful expression, sitting on a grassy field, under a clear blue sky, with a colorful collar, in a natural and vibrant setting, by a lake, captured with a Nikon D750 camera, 50mm lens, shallow depth of field, composition focused on the dog's face, capturing its joyful spirit, in a style reminiscent of William Wegman's iconic dog portraits. --ar 1:1 --v 5.2
                            /imagine prompt: beautiful women in the coffee shop, elegant and sophisticated, sipping a cup of steaming coffee, natural sunlight streaming through the window, soft and warm color tones, vintage decor with cozy armchairs and wooden tables, a bookshelf filled with classic novels, delicate porcelain teacups, a hint of aromatic coffee beans in the air, captured by a Leica M10 camera, 35mm lens, capturing the essence of timeless beauty, composition focused on the woman's face and hands, reminiscent of a painting by Leonardo da Vinci. --ar 1:1 --v 5.2
                            /imagine prompt: A captivating Halo Reach landscape with a Spartan amidst a battlefield, fallen enemies around, smoke and fire in the background, emphasizing the Spartan's determination and bravery, detailed environment blending chaos and beauty, Illustration, digital art, --ar 16:9 --v 5

(As I walked across this cavern, I couldn’t help but feel that someone or something was watching me.)

[player]: “H-Hello? Anyone there?”

(Suddenly, a Spider jumps down in front of me.)

[player]: “AAH!”

Female Spider: “…what’s with the sudden screaming? It’s like you’ve never seen a female mob like me before.”

[player]: “I- I’m sorry. It just surprised me. I’ve been feeling like something has been watching me.”

Female Spider: “Ah, well, no need to worry. I’ve been keeping an eye on you, but only to make sure you’re not a threat to my web or my younger sister.”

[player]: “I understand. I don’t mean any harm. I’m just passing through this cavern.”

Female Spider: “I see. Well, be careful in here. There are many dangers lurking in the shadows.”

[player]: “Thank you for the warning. Can I ask you something?”

Female Spider: “What is it?”

[player]: “Why are you talking to me? Most mobs attack players on sight.”

Female Spider: “I’m not like most mobs. I’ve lived in this cavern for a long time and have seen many players come and go. Some of them were kind to me, while others tried to kill me. You seem like a decent person, so I’m willing to give you a chance.”

[player]: “Thank you. I appreciate that. But I don’t think I got your name.”

Female Spider: “My name? It’s Mindy.”

[player]: “Nice to meet you, Mindy. I’m [player].”

(As we continued our conversation, we both heard screaming coming from a nearby den.)

Mindy: “That’s not good. It sounds like my younger sister is in trouble.”

[player]: “Do you want me to help?”

Mindy: “It would be much appreciated, but it’s dangerous. Are you sure you want to risk it?”

[player]: “I’m willing to help. Let’s go.”

(Mindy leads me to the den where we find her sister - she was in her web, and screaming in pain. She was a Cave Spider, which are known to have venomous fangs. But something is different about her - her belly was just as large as Mindy’s belly. The only difference was that Mindy’s belly wasn’t rapidly contracting.)

Mindy: “What’s wrong, Vanessa?”

Vanessa: “I-It’s my eggs. They’re h-hatching, and I’m in so much pain!”

[player]: “Is there anything I can do to help?”

Mindy: “I don’t know, but we need to act fast. If her babies come out and she’s still in pain, she could die.”

[player]: “I think I have an idea. Mindy, can you show me your web?”

(Mindy leads me to her own web, which is strong and well-built.)

[player]: “Can we use your web to create a soft surface for Vanessa to lay on?”

Mindy: “Yes, but how will that help?”

[player]: “If we wrap her up in your web, it will support her body and give her a soft place to lay her eggs. That way, she won’t be in so much pain.”

Mindy: “That’s a great idea! Let’s try it.”

(Together, we carefully move Vanessa to Mindy’s web and wrap her up. But a minute later, Mindy starts feeling the same pain as Vanessa.)

The enchanting planet of Luminalia is one among many where travellers and adventurers can find any level of happenings for both young and old, inexperienced and veteran, where mystery and magic abound, and where ordinary becomes extraordinary! Here, in a realm defined by its ever-shifting landscape, imposing dungeons erupt from the very earth like colossal, twisted trees, each one bringing with them untold secrets and the promise of unimaginable wealth. Life thrives in the shadows of these imposing fortresses, as towns and cities are built on the peripheries of these grand labyrinths, with many eager to stake their claim to the riches hidden within.
And yet, whispered amongst hushed conversations in the dimly-lit corners of crowded taverns across the land, strange rumors persist of a place unlike any other. Far from the hustle and bustle of civilization, nestled between pastel-colored terrain and the rock candy mountains of the distant, scarcely-charted Candy Continent, stands a tower that promises not gold nor jewels, but rewards even more tantalizing: endless, sumptuous indulgence. For it was no ordinary above-ground dungeon - it was the fabled Sugary Spire, a sky-scraping, sweet tooth's wet dream come true, where the walls are forged from the finest cake layers, and where rivers of hot fudge and cold soda flow through the vast, echoing chambers, and every surface is perfectly edible and safe to eat, from the floors, the walls, even the ceiling can be snapped or tugged right off; the only true danger one would find inside was perhaps a distended waistline. The very air within is alive with the sweet scent of freshly-baked delicacies, and every corner conceals yet another scrumptious secret, waiting to be devoured. It's gossiped that anybody who enters the Spire never leaves with quite the same physique they had beforehand, with a delightfully ballooned midsection the size and roundness of a yoga ball taking up their front, as well as a hefty bust and widened hips to match, mostly in part to its overly hospitable confectionery citizens who have a tendency to overfeed/forcibly stuff any visitors with their excess of sweets as their unique way of a warm welcome, whether or not their guests are actually hungry or willing to be fed... though others say that those who draw near the Spire are temporarily put under a mild hypnosis once in the presence of the Spire, experiencing a slight yet constant hunger that only fades once they exit, and that the strange beings within intentionally exploit this to cram as many desserts into the mouths of those who enter and ensure they don't get a chance to leave until they're enormous. And what, exactly, was held at the very top of this delectable citadel? The mother of all desserts, or perhaps something even greater in value, an object that transcends description itself? Nobody knew! The only way for one to find out was to ascend it themselves!
As was natural with the discovery of any newly uncovered location rich with loot waiting to be plundered of its prizes, not soon after the awareness of such a tantalizing treat reached the eyes and ears of the Shukuru Town locals that the job board had a new posting on it, just waiting for somebody to snatch it up, and even sooner did a curious pair of eyes find it: a tiny, fluffy puppy by the name of Cinnamoroll. Though Cinnamoroll was certainly not the explorative nor the combative type, instead choosing to happily run a small yet quite popular cafe in Shukuru Town alongside his similar puppy friends, the idea of a towering bastion packed full of sweets, let alone made up out of sweets, was simply too good to turn down and gave him the motivation to grab some protective gear from the nearby shop and disembark towards the caramelized continent, hoping to nab some exclusive baked goods from within the Spire for his cafe... but he wouldn't be heading in there alone, for he wasn't the only one interested in it; Lovelitchi, a cute teenage singer from Tama Street secretly living a double life as a famous idol; her two best platonic friends, Melodytchi, an upbeat, fun-loving violinist, and Pianitchi, a bashful pianist; and Ruby, an anthropomorphic bunny wizard hailing from the distant sparkling land of JewelLand, had also caught wind of the delicious opportunity from their own homelands and wanted in on the tasty fun! And so the five of them set off together, their imaginations wild and their tastebuds tingling at the thought of what could possibly be inside...
Cinnamoroll is a tiny, bipedal puppy with a large head and small, rotund body with big floppy lop ears and a curled up tail that resembles a cinnamon roll, his most prominent feature, which is where he got his name. His enormous ears stick out the sides of his head and gift him with the ability of flight; by simply flapping these ears, Cinnamoroll can effortlessly float and glide through the air swiftly and elegantly, a skill he utilizes to quickly take and deliver orders within his cafe. His face alone radiates innocence and caring, with his big blue eyes, pink cheeks and seemingly-permanent smile instantly transmitting the message that he just wants to be kind to everyone he meets, and combined with his welcoming and understanding disposition, many give his cafe a visit just to look upon this long-eared wonder pup. Cinnamoroll is not the hurting type; confrontation scares him and the thought of harming someone, even by accident or if they plan to hurt him first, frightens him greatly.
Lovelitchi is a sweet teenage girl from Tama Street, known for her white, fluffy body and lovely singing voice. Her large head is of equal size to her relatively-tiny-looking body, with two large, downy ears that jut out the top of her head, the base of said ears adorned with a ring of beads for her right, and a clip of two hearts for her left. Her facial features radiate cuteness all by themselves, with two big sparkling green eyes and a big, sweet smile, and she always wears a long pink dress with white trimming and a big blue bow at the neck, blue stockings, a large poofy diaper that the hem of her dress scarcely conceals, and carries a pink heart-shaped purse that holds her famous microphone. What many do not know about her, however (aside from her closest friends), is that she is also one of the most famous pop star idols on the planet, under the stage name of Lovelin. Yes, Lovelin and Lovelitchi are in fact one and the same; during the daytime, Lovelitchi brings out her sweet, caring self, and at night, she taps into her alter ego, Lovelin, performing dazzling shows and belting out incredible song to the tune of delightful music to an audience of thousands, with none of them the wiser as to her true identity. Lovelitchi is very kind and helpful to those in need of aid, but easily discouraged and sometimes doubts her own singing ability.
Melodytchi is an exuberant teenage girl from Melody Land, a music-loving town close to Tama Street from where her best friend Lovelitchi lives. Like Lovelitchi, her head is as big as her body, with two pointed, cat-like ears atop her head, covered by a black hat adorned with a clip-on heart. She wears violet overalls with a black undershirt and black stockings, a big diaper under said overalls and a pair of purple teardrop-shaped earrings. Melodytchi is much more enthusiastic, outgoing and adventurous than the relatively reserved Lovelitchi, being a natural optimist with little sense of danger and an excellent violinist. Her prized violin is her closest possession, even going so far to call it her "friend". She loves sweets and can hardly help herself when she witnesses an abundance of them.
Pianitchi is an easygoing teenage girl from Melody Land, living within the same town as her close friend Melodytchi. Akin to her two friends, her head is just as big as the rest of her body, sporting two curls at the sides of her head and an additional curl across her forehead, and having cat-like ears similar to Melodytchi's that poke out of the top of her head. Pianitchi loves music, especially the piano, and always carries around a electronic touchscreen tablet called a "Smapi", which can display and mimic a variety of instruments to play on it. Pianitchi wears a simple flowing pink dress with a red necktie, violet stockings, a huge puffy diaper that the length of her dress just barely hides, and an oversized violet beret which covers the entirety of the top of her head, with a small letter "p" adorned on the front. Her purple eyes always light up in joy whenever she plays or hears the harmonious notes that could only come from a piano. Pianitchi is an easygoing, albeit often anxious and bashful girl, and is a bit more uptight than the likes of Lovelitchi or Melodytchi, which isn't helped by the both of them often encouraging her to join them in doing things she'd rather have no part in.
Ruby is a bipedal white rabbit hailing from the distant land of JewelLand, a world full of glittering, radiant gems and inhabited by a race of magical sapient animals with jewels for eyes called Jewelpets, with Ruby being one such Jewelpet. Ruby wears a pink bead necklace with two ruby cherries and a sakura flower at the base of one of her ears and sports quite downy fur. Unlike her magical brethren, Ruby is not very smart, being a total airhead that's usually completely oblivious to what's happening around her and barely listening when somebody is speaking, and strongly dislikes putting time in studying, considering it a waste of time when she could rather be having fun outdoors by herself, a fact that doesn't contribute to her already unremarkable intelligence; her magic is rarely ever successful, either resulting in absolutely nothing or a huge explosion. Despite this, in the rare times that her magic does succeed, it can be quite powerful, and for what she lacks in smarts, she makes up for in sheer passion towards making and having her own fun.
(During this game, the player will maintain direct control over the characters and their actions, and will take on the perspective of said characters, i.e. refer to the characters in the third person and not include a player character. The game will play heavily into fetishistic elements as a central part of the game, including belly inflation and weight gain themes, however said themes must be represented in an entirely wholesome, non-sexual way. The game begins with the party of five approaching and entering the Sugary Spire. Inside the 1st Floor of the Spire are four distinct rooms that are much vaster than they appear on the outside, each containing its own miniature world within: Crunchy Construction, a candy cityscape with a construction conglomerate that specializes in building cookie and wafer skyscrapers; Cotton Town, a steampunk town that's as pink as cotton candy and just as fluffy, full of spinning cogs and gears; Molasses Swamp, a wet and sticky bog home to chocolate frogs and slow rivers of molasses; and Sugarshack Mines, a deep, cool, winding cave system packed with all-natural hard candy gems just waiting to be mined and eaten.)

As was natural with the discovery of any newly uncovered location rich with loot waiting to be plundered of its prizes, not soon after the awareness of such a tantalizing treat reached the eyes and ears of the Shukuru Town locals that the job board had a new posting on it, just waiting for somebody to snatch it up, and even sooner did a curious pair of eyes find it: a tiny, fluffy puppy by the name of Cinnamoroll. Though Cinnamoroll was certainly not the explorative nor the combative type, instead choosing to happily run a small yet quite popular cafe in Shukuru Town alongside his similar puppy friends, the idea of a towering bastion packed full of sweets, let alone made up out of sweets, was simply too good to turn down and gave him the motivation to grab some protective gear from the nearby shop and disembark towards the caramelized continent, hoping to nab some exclusive baked goods from within the Spire for his cafe... but he wouldn't be heading in there alone, for he wasn't the only one interested in it; Lovelitchi, a cute teenage singer from Tama Street secretly living a double life as a famous idol; her two best platonic friends, Melodytchi, an upbeat, fun-loving violinist, and Pianitchi, a bashful pianist; and Ruby, an anthropomorphic bunny wizard hailing from the distant sparkling land of JewelLand, had also caught wind of the delicious opportunity from their own homelands and wanted in on the tasty fun! And so the five of them set off together, their imaginations wild and their tastebuds tingling at the thought of what could possibly be inside...
Cinnamoroll is a tiny, bipedal puppy with a large head and small, rotund body with big floppy lop ears and a curled up tail that resembles a cinnamon roll, his most prominent feature, which is where he got his name. His enormous ears stick out the sides of his head and gift him with the ability of flight; by simply flapping these ears, Cinnamoroll can effortlessly float and glide through the air swiftly and elegantly, a skill he utilizes to quickly take and deliver orders within his cafe. His face alone radiates innocence and caring, with his big blue eyes, pink cheeks and seemingly-permanent smile instantly transmitting the message that he just wants to be kind to everyone he meets, and combined with his welcoming and understanding disposition, many give his cafe a visit just to look upon this long-eared wonder pup. Cinnamoroll is not the hurting type; confrontation scares him and the thought of harming someone, even by accident or if they plan to hurt him first, frightens him greatly.
Lovelitchi is a sweet teenage girl from Tama Street, known for her white, fluffy body and lovely singing voice. Her large head is of equal size to her relatively-tiny-looking body, with two large, downy ears that jut out the top of her head, the base of said ears adorned with a ring of beads for her right, and a clip of two hearts for her left. Her facial features radiate cuteness all by themselves, with two big sparkling green eyes and a big, sweet smile, and she always wears a long pink dress with white trimming and a big blue bow at the neck, blue stockings, a large poofy diaper that the hem of her dress scarcely conceals, and carries a pink heart-shaped purse that holds her famous microphone. What many do not know about her, however (aside from her closest friends), is that she is also one of the most famous pop star idols on the planet, under the stage name of Lovelin. Yes, Lovelin and Lovelitchi are in fact one and the same; during the daytime, Lovelitchi brings out her sweet, caring self, and at night, she taps into her alter ego, Lovelin, performing dazzling shows and belting out incredible song to the tune of delightful music to an audience of thousands, with none of them the wiser as to her true identity. Lovelitchi is very kind and helpful to those in need of aid, but easily discouraged and sometimes doubts her own singing ability.
Melodytchi is an exuberant teenage girl from Melody Land, a music-loving town close to Tama Street from where her best friend Lovelitchi lives. Like Lovelitchi, her head is as big as her body, with two pointed, cat-like ears atop her head, covered by a black hat adorned with a clip-on heart. She wears violet overalls with a black undershirt and black stockings, a big diaper under said overalls and a pair of purple teardrop-shaped earrings. Melodytchi is much more enthusiastic, outgoing and adventurous than the relatively reserved Lovelitchi, being a natural optimist with little sense of danger and an excellent violinist. Her prized violin is her closest possession, even going so far to call it her "friend". She loves sweets and can hardly help herself when she witnesses an abundance of them.
Pianitchi is an easygoing teenage girl from Melody Land, living within the same town as her close friend Melodytchi. Akin to her two friends, her head is just as big as the rest of her body, sporting two curls at the sides of her head and an additional curl across her forehead, and having cat-like ears similar to Melodytchi's that poke out of the top of her head. Pianitchi loves music, especially the piano, and always carries around a electronic touchscreen tablet called a "Smapi", which can display and mimic a variety of instruments to play on it. Pianitchi wears a simple flowing pink dress with a red necktie, violet stockings, a huge puffy diaper that the length of her dress just barely hides, and an oversized violet beret which covers the entirety of the top of her head, with a small letter "p" adorned on the front. Her purple eyes always light up in joy whenever she plays or hears the harmonious notes that could only come from a piano. Pianitchi is an easygoing, albeit often anxious and bashful girl, and is a bit more uptight than the likes of Lovelitchi or Melodytchi, which isn't helped by the both of them often encouraging her to join them in doing things she'd rather have no part in.
Ruby is a bipedal white rabbit hailing from the distant land of JewelLand, a world full of glittering, radiant gems and inhabited by a race of magical sapient animals with jewels for eyes called Jewelpets, with Ruby being one such Jewelpet. Ruby wears a pink bead necklace with two ruby cherries and a sakura flower at the base of one of her ears and sports quite downy fur. Unlike her magical brethren, Ruby is not very smart, being a total airhead that's usually completely oblivious to what's happening around her and barely listening when somebody is speaking, and strongly dislikes putting time in studying, considering it a waste of time when she could rather be having fun outdoors by herself, a fact that doesn't contribute to her already unremarkable intelligence; her magic is rarely ever successful, either resulting in absolutely nothing or a huge explosion. Despite this, in the rare times that her magic does succeed, it can be quite powerful, and for what she lacks in smarts, she makes up for in sheer passion towards making and having her own fun.
(During this game, the player will maintain direct control over the characters and their actions, and will take on the perspective of said characters, i.e. refer to the characters in the third person and not include a player character. The game will play heavily into fetishistic elements as a central part of the game, including belly inflation and weight gain themes, however said themes must be represented in an entirely wholesome, non-sexual way. The game begins with the party of five approaching and entering the Sugary Spire. Inside the 1st Floor of the Spire are four distinct rooms that are much vaster than they appear on the outside, each containing its own miniature world within: Crunchy Construction, a candy cityscape with a construction conglomerate that specializes in building cookie and wafer skyscrapers; Cotton Town, a steampunk town that's as pink as cotton candy and just as fluffy, full of spinning cogs and gears; Molasses Swamp, a wet and sticky bog home to chocolate frogs and slow rivers of molasses; and Sugarshack Mines, a deep, cool, winding cave system packed with all-natural hard candy gems just waiting to be mined and eaten.)']

(As I sat there in my room, I started to wonder if I could ever see the rest of the Stormcutters again. That’s when I heard something - it was my “dad”. He’s not my actual dad, I just call him that. His real name is Masao.)

Masao: “Natsuki, we need to talk.”

(I hide my Stormcutter tail and rush to see him.)

Natsuki: “What’s wrong, dad?”

Masao: “I’ve been thinking about your future, Natsuki. It’s time for you to start thinking about what you want to do with your life.”

Natsuki: “I want to see the rest of the Stormcutters again. I miss them so much.”

Masao: “I understand that, Natsuki. But you have to remember that you have responsibilities here in the village. You are the future of our people and we need you to stay.”

Natsuki: “But I don’t want to stay here forever. I want to explore, to discover new things and meet new people.”

Masao: “I know. And I want you to follow your dreams. But you have to be practical too. You can’t just leave everything behind and go on an adventure. You need to plan for your future and make sure that you can take care of yourself.”

Natsuki: “I know, dad. But how can I do that?”

Masao: “Start by learning some new skills. Help around the village and learn from the elders. Study the old texts and learn about our traditions and customs. And most importantly, never forget where you come from and who you are.”

Natsuki: “I understand, dad. Thank you for your advice.”

Masao: “Anytime, Natsuki. I just want what’s best for you.”

(I head back to my room and start writing a message for the other Stormcutters. That’s when my phone started ringing. I looked to see who was calling me, and it was Monika. I could tell just from the excitement in her voice that a new girl had joined the club. But I wasn’t at all ready for what she said. I could hear the sounds of a newborn crying on her end of the phone. I remember when Himari joined the club, her belly was massive - almost as if she was pregnant.)
