And more importantly, NOTHING could get past my defenses - Aegises in the skies, Lacedons and Dwellers in the water, Astaroths serving as sentries on the ground, about 500 Rooststalkers, and even two Royal Reds guarding my front door.)

[player]: "With these defenses, I'm practically unstoppable!"

(Just then, I noticed an arrow lodged in my window.)

[player]: "This...isn't my arrow."

(I heard footsteps just outside the base. I looked to see who it was - and it was a strange girl. Her eyes and hair were gray, and she had a bow in her hand. Her clothing resembled a Skeleton mob, which revealed her chest. Her belly was massive, but I didn't bother to ask her about it.)

Female Skeleton: "Uh...h-hello..."

(I could tell she was nervous just from the tone of her voice. But how did she get past my defenses, even my two Royal Reds?)

How many Wow words do I have in this text:

Benvolio, as quiet as the still night air, peered through the heavy iron doors that guarded the inside of the old, sacred burial tomb of the Capulets, to examine the loud commotion that could be heard from as far away as the old Stone Pines that formed an organised ring of symmetry outside of the tomb. Which was usually so silent that the scutter of a mouse could break it. The inside horrified Benvolio. To his utter horror he could see the fresh, pale corpse of his cousin Romeo crumpled on the stony floor of the tomb, surrounded by Capulets-the sworn enemies of his kin, The Montagues -with their longswords held in an offensive position as if they had just been attacked. 

Benvolio fled the scene to his horse that he parked in the shadows of the stone pines hidden away from visible sight to report the death of his cousin Romeo to Lord Montague. As he rode his horse through the cold night to his destination tears led down his cheeks as he thought about the horrible scene he had only witnessed moments before.  As Benvolio reached the front entrance to the large, stone-brick castle of the Montague family, he forced his horse to a halt and began to make his way to the room of the sleeping Lord Montague, Romeo’s Father. Benvolio ran over to Lord Montagues side and shook him awake while screaming, “Lord Montague, wake up! It is I, Benvolio, and I come with grave news! Your son Romeo has been murdered in cold blood by the house of Capulets!” As Lord Montague awoke confusion took over his expression. “Do not come at me in the middle of the night with this daft misinformation Benvolio”, mumbled Lord Montage while still drowsy from sleep. “My son Romeo is asleep in his room at this moment”. 

“It is true my Lord!” Benvolio screamed as tears began to leave his bloodshot eyes. “I saw Romeo’s lifeless face in the tomb of the Capulets”. Dread filled Lord Montagues eyes as the information overcame him. “I cannot believe my only son has been murdered by those dreaded Capulets”. Lord Montague said while pressing his palms against his forehead. “Benvolio, we must rid the world of Capulet vermin, once and for all, for our families honour and for Romeos sake.”

Lord Montage leapt out of his horse hair, king size bed and equipped himself with his steel longsword, that was embedded with a large emblem which represented the Montague family, and pulled his long blue cloak over his shoulders. “Gather an Army Benvolio! We will set out for the castle of the Capulet’s at dawn.” Lord Montague yelled out to the panicking Benvolio. 

Benvolio begun to run around the extravagant interior of the Montague castle and urban sprawl that surrounded the castle waking up fellow Montagues to gear up and to meet at the castle walls to set out for a final battle against the Capulet. By the time the sun began to rise every Montague, including the women and children, was equipped with a weapon and was ready to follow Lord Montague, possibly to their death. 

As the Montague army set out for the Capulet castle word had already made it to Lord Capulet that the Montague’s had planned to wipe out his family name and so he began to ready his own army to defend against their enemy.

After an hours trek to the Capulet castle the Montague army was only a mere door away from their enemy. “This is where the Capulet family ends! The Montague family will leave here victorious!” Lord Montague yelled as he readied to siege the castle. As Lord Montague placed his hand upon the large iron handle of the castle doors, a rain of arrows came flying down from Capulet archers stationed high up on top of the castle walls, killing a fair amount of Montagues, including Benvolio. A fierce battle then commenced between the Montagues and Capulets, with many of each party being murdered.  Both the House of Montague and Capulet fought long into the day with old silver longswords and other weaponry such crossbows and knives. The murder and violence continued until only two people remained; Lord Montague and Lord Capulet. 

Both ran at each other across the body littered courtyard of the battlefield, with their Longsword embedded with their red and blue family emblem dripping with blood of their enemy. When they reached at a midpoint their swords clashed and orange sparks flew off the tips of their blades and fell to the floor. One final swing was taken by both Lord Montague and Lord Capulet which resulted in both taking a fatal blow to the skull, ending the bloodline of the Montagues and Capulets.

(In the clubroom…)

Natsuki: “Honestly, I’m getting worried about her.”

Monika: “Natsuki, I know you’re worried about her. But…this is the first time you’re not freaking out.”

Yuri: (entering the clubroom) “Who are you two waiting for?”

Natsuki: “We’re waiting for Sayori. She hasn’t been herself lately and we’re concerned about her.”

Yuri: “Oh, I see. It’s nice that you’re both worried about her. Maybe you should try talking to her and see if she opens up about what is bothering her.”

Monika: “We’ve tried, but she just keeps brushing it off and saying she’s fine. It’s really frustrating.”

Yuri: “Sometimes people just need time and patience. She’ll open up when she’s ready. In the meantime, we can still show our support and let her know we’re here for her.”

Natsuki: “I guess you’re right. It’s just hard to see her like this.”

Yuri: “I understand how you feel, Natsuki. It’s never easy when someone you care about is going through a tough time. Just remember that we’re all here for her, and we’ll get through this together.”

Monika: “Thanks, Yuri. Your words of encouragement mean a lot. Let’s just hope she starts feeling better soon.”

(They all sit in silence for a moment, hoping for the best for Sayori.)

(Meanwhile, at Sayori’s house…)

(Sayori is laying down on her bed, and very obviously in the final stages of labor - so there was no way to take her to a hospital.)

(Sayori’s breathing is heavy and her face is covered in sweat. She clenches her fists, trying to manage the pain.)

Sayori: (whispering to herself) “I can do this… I have to stay strong…”

(Suddenly, a sharp contraction hits her and she lets out a small cry of pain. She takes deep breaths, trying to calm herself.)

(Sayori’s phone buzzes with a notification. She reaches over and sees that it’s a text from Natsuki.)

Natsuki (text): “Hey, Sayori. We’re all really worried about you. Can you please let us know how you’re doing?”

(Sayori looks at the text, tears welling up in her eyes. She wants to respond, but the pain intensifies and she’s unable to gather the strength.)

(Sayori’s phone buzzes again, this time with a call from Monika. She hesitates for a moment before answering.)

Sayori: (weakly) “H-Hello…?”

Monika: (worried) “Sayori, are you okay? We’ve been trying to reach you for a while. What’s happening?”

Sayori: (struggling) “I… I’m in labor… I didn’t know who to call…”

Monika: (concerned) “Oh my gosh, Sayori! Why didn’t you tell us earlier? We would have helped you!”

Sayori: (teary-eyed) “I didn’t want to burden anyone… I thought I could handle it on my own…” (starting to feel another contraction hit) “AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAHHHHHH!!!”

Monika: (panicking) “Sayori, stay on the line! We’re coming over right now, okay? Just hold on!”

(Sayori gasps for breath, still in immense pain.)

Yuri: (joining the call) “Sayori, we’re here for you. Don’t worry, help is on the way.”

Natsuki: (also joining the call) “Sayori, we care about you so much. We want to support you through this. You’re not alone, okay?”

(Sayori releases a sob, feeling a mix of fear, relief, and gratitude.)

Sayori: “T-Thank you, everyone… I… I really need you right now…”

Monika: “Don’t worry, Sayori. We’ll be there as fast as we can. Just stay on the line and try to breathe calmly, okay?”

(Sayori nods weakly, focusing on their words of support amidst the pain.)

(At Sayori’s house…)

(The door bursts open as Monika, Natsuki, and Yuri rush in, their faces filled with concern.)

Monika: “Sayori, where are you? We’re here!”

(Sayori’s voice echoes weakly from the bedroom.)

Sayori: “I-I’m in here…”

(The girls quickly make their way to the bedroom, finding Sayori lying on the bed, tears streaming down her face.)

Yuri: “Sayori, we’re so sorry. We should have realized something was wrong sooner.”

Natsuki: “Yeah, we should’ve been there for you when you needed us. We’re really sorry.”

Sayori: (weakly) “It’s okay… I didn’t tell anyone… It’s not your fault…”

Monika: “Sayori, you shouldn’t have suffered alone. We’re here now, and we’re going to help you through this.”

Sayori: “Thanks, everyone. Let’s bring my baby into the world together.”

(The girls rally around Sayori, offering her words of comfort and support. They help her into a comfortable position as her contractions continue.)

Sayori: “They’re getting closer together, Monika!”

Monika: “Don’t worry, Sayori. Just keep breathing and stay focused. We’ll be right by your side the whole time.”

Natsuki: “You’re doing great, Sayori. Just remember to take deep breaths and stay as relaxed as you can.”

Yuri: “We’re here for you, Sayori. Just keep pushing through each contraction. You’re incredibly strong.”

(Sayori continues to endure each contraction with the support of her friends. Hours pass, and finally, the urgent need to push fills Sayori’s body.)

(I still missed my old friends back before I joined the literature club. Ayano always calmed my nerves when I went crazy for boys, and feeling Kokona’s triplets move around was exhilarating. Just then, I got a phone call - it was Kokona!)

Kokona: “Hey, Yuri! Long time no talk!”

(I was thrilled to hear Kokona’s voice again. Even though it’s been 10 months since Kokona got pregnant, I could hear several things that indicated she was in the delivery room.)

Yuri: “Kokona! Oh wow, it’s so good to hear from you! How have you been? And… are you in the delivery room?”

Kokona: “Yeah, you know me, always multitasking! The doctors say it’s almost time for me to give birth. I just wanted to take a moment to catch up with you before the big moment.”

Yuri: “That’s incredible, Kokona! I’m so excited for you. How have you been feeling throughout your pregnancy? Is everything going well?”

Kokona: “Thank you, Yuri! Overall, it’s been quite the journey. There have been ups and downs, moments of joy and moments of discomfort. But knowing that I’ll soon be holding my little ones in my arms makes it all worth it. And feeling the triplets move around inside me is the most amazing feeling.”

Yuri: “I can imagine. It must be such a unique experience to carry three lives within you. I’m really happy for you, Kokona. You’ve always been so caring and loving, and I have no doubt you’ll be a wonderful mother.”

Kokona: “Aw, thank you, Yuri. That means a lot to me. I hope I can live up to your expectations. Oh, by the way, have you been doing well since we last saw each other? How’s life at the literature club?”

Yuri: “Life at the literature club has been… interesting. It’s been a great opportunity for me to explore my love for literature and creativity. The other girls are amazing, and we’ve become quite a close-knit group. But I have to admit, I do miss spending time with my old friends like you and Ayano. You two always had a way of calming my nerves and understanding me.”

Kokona: “I understand, Yuri. Change can be difficult, and it’s natural to miss what we once had. But remember, friendships can evolve and grow, even if we’re not physically together. Just because we’re not in the same place doesn’t mean we can’t still support each other.”

Yuri: “You’re right, Kokona. I shouldn’t let distance or change diminish the value of our friendship. I’m really grateful to have you in my life, even if we don’t see each other as often. And I’m always here for you, no matter what.”

Kokona: “That means the world to me, Yuri. Thank you for being such an amazing friend. And don’t worry, once things settle down a bit with the babies, we’ll definitely find a way to catch up properly. Speaking of which, I think the first triplet is about to arrive!”

Yuri: “Oh my goodness, Kokona! That’s so exciting! Take deep breaths and stay calm, you’re going to do great. I’ll be sending you all my positive thoughts and well wishes.”

Kokona: “Thank you, Yuri. I really appreciate it. I’ll keep you updated on everything. And don’t worry, I’ll make sure to save a special moment for when we can meet up and properly catch up. I’m sure the babies would love to meet Aunt Yuri.”

Yuri: “Aunt Yuri, I like the sound of that. Please give the little ones a gentle pat for me. I can’t wait to hear all about them and their unique personalities. You’re going to be an amazing mom, Kokona. I just know it.”

Kokona: “Thank you so much, Yuri. Your support means everything to me. I’ll make sure to keep you involved in this journey every step of the way. And remember, even though things might change, our friendship will always hold a special place in my heart.”

Yuri: “And mine too, Kokona. No matter what happens, our bond will remain strong. Take care of yourself and those beautiful little ones. I’ll be eagerly waiting to hear all the wonderful news. Good luck, Kokona. You’ve got this.”

Kokona: “Thank you, Yuri. You’re the best. I’ll talk to you soon, okay?”

Yuri: “Definitely, Kokona. Looking forward to it. Take care of yourself and stay strong. Sending lots of love your way.”

(With a final exchange of well wishes and reassurances, Kokona and I hung up the phone. I couldn’t help but feel a mix of emotions - excitement for Kokona and the upcoming arrival of the triplets, but also a longing for the familiarity of my old friendships. Nevertheless, I knew that even though things had changed, the bonds of friendship remained strong. And when I arrived at the clubroom, I saw somebody I didn’t expect - it was Ayano! She was talking to Monika, Sayori, and Natsuki - almost as if she wanted to join the literature club, even though Natsuki looked around 7 months pregnant. I couldn’t believe it - for the first time ever since MC’s death, I felt overjoyed to meet my old friend again.)

Ayano: “Yuri! It’s been so long, I’ve missed you!”

Yuri: “Ayano! I can’t believe it’s really you. I’ve missed you too!”

(Ayano and I hugged tightly, both of us holding back tears of joy.)

Ayano: “I’ve been wanting to come back and see you all for a while now. Life has been really tough since MC’s passing, but I’ve realized that isolating myself isn’t the answer. I need my friends, I need you, Yuri.”

Yuri: “I’m so glad you reached that realization, Ayano. We’ve all been worried about you. But I’m really proud of you for taking this step. And let me just say, you have no idea how much we’ve missed you.”

Monika: “Ayano, it’s such a pleasant surprise to see you here. The literature club isn’t the same without you. We would love for you to join us again.”

Ayano: “Thank you, Monika. I would love to join the literature club again. I’ve really missed our discussions and activities.”

Sayori: “Ayano, I’m so happy you’re back! We missed your calming presence and unique insights. Plus, we need your help with planning our next club activity. It’s going to be so much fun!”

Natsuki: “Yeah, yeah! It’s about time you came back, Ayano. Nobody else can beat you in our manga debates. Welcome back to the literature club!”

Ayano: “Thank you all so much for welcoming me back with open arms. It means the world to me. I’ve missed you guys more than I can express.”

(As the club members continued to chat and catch up, I couldn’t help but feel an overwhelming sense of happiness and gratitude. It was as if a piece of my heart that had been missing for so long had finally returned. Despite the ups and downs we had all experienced, our bond as friends had remained strong.)

Yuri: “Welcome back, Ayano. I’m so glad to have you here with us again. Let’s create beautiful memories together, just like old times.”

Ayano: “Thank you, Yuri. I’m excited to make new memories with you all. Let’s treasure our friendship and the precious moments we share.”

(With the reunion of Ayano and the renewed bond between us, I knew that no matter what challenges lay ahead, we would always have each other for support. The literature club, now complete once again, was ready to embrace the future and continue growing together. After some time, all of us went to see Kokona in the hospital - she had finally given birth to the triplets. As we entered Kokona’s hospital room, we were greeted by the sight of three tiny bundles wrapped in soft blankets. Kokona herself looked tired but radiant, a proud smile on her face.)

Kokona: “Hey, everyone! Come meet my little miracles.”

(Ayano, Monika, Sayori, Natsuki, and I gathered around Kokona’s bed, each of us taking turns in holding one of the babies. They were delicate and precious, their tiny fingers and toes captivating us all.)

Monika: “They’re absolutely adorable, Kokona. Congratulations! What are their names?”

Kokona: “Thank you, Monika. Well, this little guy here is Kazuki, and the two girls are Hana and Sakura. I wanted their names to reflect their individuality and beauty.”

Ayano: “Those names are perfect, Kokona. They suit them so well.”

Sayori: “Look at their tiny little faces! They’re like little angels.”

Natsuki: “Wow, being an aunt is going to be so much fun now that I have three new nieces and nephews!”

Yuri: “They’re truly blessings, Kokona. I’m so happy for you. They already have such loving and strong-hearted parents.”

Kokona: “Thank you, everyone. I can’t express how grateful I am to have you all here with me. You’ve been there for me through thick and thin, and now you’re here to celebrate this joyous moment with me.”

(We spent the rest of the afternoon in Kokona’s hospital room, talking, laughing, and sharing stories. The triplets were peacefully sleeping, their presence bringing a sense of tranquility to the room. It was a beautiful reminder of the power of friendship and the enduring bond we shared.)

Ayano: “Kokona, thank you for allowing us to be a part of this special day. The triplets are lucky to have you as their mother.”

Kokona: “No, thank you, Ayano. And thank you all. I couldn’t have asked for better friends. You’ve been my rock throughout this journey, and I know you’ll continue to be there for me and my little ones.”

Monika: “That’s what friends are for, Kokona. We’ll always be here, supporting and loving you. And now, these little ones too.”

Sayori: “Yeah, we’re like one big family, right? The four of us may not be related by blood, but our bond is just as strong.”

Natsuki: “Agreed. And with Ayano back, our family is complete once more.”

Yuri: “Let’s cherish our friendship, both old and new, and the beautiful connections we’ve formed in the literature club. Together, we can create a future filled with love, support, and endless memories.”

(The room filled with warmth and love as we continued to celebrate the arrival of the triplets and the rekindling of our friendship. But then I noticed that there were about five babies moving inside Natsuki’s belly.)

Yuri: “Natsuki, are you… expecting too?”

Natsuki: “Surprise! Yeah, I found out a few weeks ago that I’m pregnant too! Looks like these little ones couldn’t wait to join the party.”

Ayano: “That’s incredible, Natsuki! Congratulations! I guess the literature club will be filled with even more tiny members now. But…how many babies are moving around in there?”

Natsuki: “Haha, I know, right? It’s a bit overwhelming, but I couldn’t be happier. Turns out, I’m expecting quintuplets!”

Everyone: “Quintuplets?!”

Natsuki: “Yeah, I was just as shocked when I found out. But it’s an absolute blessing, and I can’t wait to meet all five of them.”

Ayano: “That’s amazing, Natsuki! We’re so happy for you.”

Monika: “Congratulations, Natsuki. This is going to be quite an adventure.”

Sayori: “Wow, Natsuki, you’re going to have your hands full. But I know you’ll be an amazing mom.”

Yuri: “Five little ones, Natsuki. That’s incredible. I can’t wait to see them all and spoil them with love.”

Natsuki: “Thank you, everyone. I’m a little nervous, but knowing that I have all of you by my side makes it easier. And hey, the more, the merrier, right?”

(As the afternoon continued, we enveloped Natsuki in a warm embrace, expressing our excitement and support for the journey ahead. The literature club had grown even bigger, and our bond as friends had only strengthened. Little did we know, these new additions to our group would bring even more joy and love into our lives. When Natsuki went for her final ultrasound before the big day, we found a sixth baby hiding behind its siblings.)

Explain why Affectors cannot create artificial gravity.

"Affectors use a principle still mysterious to Human science to create controlled forces on fermionic matter at a distance. Fermions are the particles that make up atoms (electrons, protons and neutrons), and some kinds of radiation. In this way, affector technology allowed the Antecessors to manipulate the world around them. Affectors also interact with other affectors, allowing complicated non-linear phenomena to occur that can be useful for control of an affector field.

At low intensities, affectors are invisible. High-strength dynamic affector fields tend to ionize air, leading to a purplish glow within the field volume for low levels of ionization or a bright blue-white glare for dense ionization. Affector emitters tend to glow blue. Since ionization produces ozone in a breathable atmosphere, which in turn can produce nitrogen oxides and smog, extensive use of affectors powerful enough to cause ionization can lead to air pollution. Consequently, intense affectors are often closely regulated.

Affector fields can have arbitrary shapes. Often taking the form of beams or sheets, they can zig-zag, form complex geometric patterns, and enclose odd-shaped volumes if engineered to do so.

Affector Limitations
Affectors are capable of affecting matter in many useful ways, but they are not able to do everything. For example

Artificial Gravity: Affectors cannot create true gravity. They can push and pull on matter, and with sufficient skin depth can apply a nearly uniform attraction or repulsion in a way that can simulate gravity over a limited volume, but no affector can make something weightless.
Inertial Dampening: Inertia (through mass) is a fundamental property of matter and there seems to be no way to modify it. Affectors cannot increase or reduce something's mass, or make it massless or inertia-less.
Stasis Fields: Affectors act on matter, not space-time. They can't slow down or speed up time (although they can prop open a wormhole, which in turn can perform some strange time shenanigans across the wormhole).
Interact With Light: Affectors only interact with matter, not electromagnetic fields. Light, and similar electromagnetic phenomena such as radio, microwaves, terahertz waves, infrared, ultraviolet, x-rays, and gamma rays, pass through affectors as if they are not there. The matter an affector holds can interact with light in its usual fashion, which allows an indirect ability to modify light. Affectors also do not interact with other bosonic fields, such as the W± boson, Z boson, or gluon."

content:
Rewrite the following story so Jake wish to become a girl at the end: Once upon a time in a small, sunny beach town, there lived a girl named Haley. Haley was your average teenager, full of excitement and curiosity for what her future would hold. She had always felt an undeniable affection for her best friend, Jake, who shared her admiration of the coastal landscape that shaped their childhood.

Every day seemed to blend into the next as they explored the shimmering shores, chased the fleeting sunsets, and laughed beneath the sprawling, star-studded sky. As Haley and Jake continued to grow and learn, their minds racing with the wonders and challenges of adolescence, Haley’s affection for Jake developed into love.

She loved the way he would drape his arm around her with nonchalance when they strolled along the coastline, the way his eyes widened with excitement at their shared ambitions, and his goofy grin that never failed to brighten her day. Haley longed to make her feelings known to her crush, but fear weighed her down like the heaviest of anchors.

One night, as the two friends laid side-by-side on the cool, damp sand, Haley made a silent wish upon a falling star. “If only I could find a way to make Jake love me as more than a friend,” she whispered. As the streak of light disappeared into oblivion, Haley drifted into a dreamless slumber, her heart filled with hope for what might come.

When the rays of the morning sun crawled over the horizon, Haley awoke to an intense sensation of clarity. She opened her eyes and gasped, her piercing green gaze now fixed on the most beautiful girl she had ever seen. Intrigued and befuddled, Haley took in the unfamiliar yet stunning sight: dark locks cascading over golden shoulders and eyes that held the secrets of the universe. It was as if the stars had rearranged themselves and created a new spectacle just to catch her attention.

In that instant, Haley’s world shifted dramatically. She found herself unable to peel her eyes away from the girl standing before her. She breathed deeply and realized that something had changed completely during her cosmic slumber, flipping her world upside down. The girl beside her was not just any girl; it was Isla, Jake’s older sister.

- - -

Jake stood awkwardly, the sands shifting under his feet. He could barely comprehend the change he saw in his best friend, and he couldn’t help but feel a sense of envy. Whereas he had always been close to Haley, he couldn’t deny that he wished for something more. He looked on as Haley and Isla became inseparable, their playful laughter, and flushed cheeks filling him with a heartache that was impossible to shake.

Eventually, the beautiful bond between Haley and Isla had blossomed into a captivating romantic love. Jake could not ignore the warmth that emitted from the couple, but he struggled to grapple with the bittersweet realization that Haley was no longer his. Jake questioned why Haley’s affections had strayed from him to Isla, but he knew deep down there was nothing he could do to change her heart.

As a multitude of celebrations and challenges filled their young lives, Jake witnessed with pride and hope the way Haley and Isla loved one another. The two young women discovered new adventures along the coast and beyond, hand in hand, and their happiness became almost contagious.

One balmy Saturday evening, as the sun sank behind the horizon, the trio sat together on the sand, their legs intertwined, and their gaze fixed on the painting unfolding before them. Haley and Isla’s eyes met for a moment, sharing a secret, quietly spoken love that brought a radiant smile to their faces.

Beside them, Jake sighed wistfully, feeling an equal part joy for their love and longing for the companionship he wished he could share with Haley. Then, in the remaining light of dusk, the tiniest glimmer of a falling star became visible.

Jake did not make a wish that night; instead, he silently vowed to cherish the friendships he held so dear, and the love that persisted between them all. They had found their own paths among the stars, and sometimes, that was all that mattered.
Continue the story.

content: Write a very long, coherent, elaborate, descriptive and detailed shooting script, including a background and dialogues, for a contemporary Comedy TV Series comic scene that includes a African-American woman (give her a name and describe her appearance; she shouldn't be wearing a dress, a skirt nor jeans) returning home and approaching her flat's door with a desperate urge to move her bowels. She was out all day (you may choose the activity that kept her busy all day, work or otherwise) and did not have an opportunity to relieve herself anywhere (you may specify the reason that prevented her from doing so, whether out of her own aversion of public restrooms or otherwise). When reaches the door of her flat, she realizes that she has misplaced her house key. She begins frantically calling her woman flatmate, who doesn't answer. Then, she begins frantically knocking on the door, hoping that the woman flatmate is present and might hear the knocks. Her urge escalates to the brink of eruption. Finally, the door is being unlocked, and she is greeted by the weary face of her woman flatmate African-American (give her a name and describe her appearance; she should be wearing an outfit that is adequate for napping), who was apparently napping this whole time. Before the woman flatmate fully swung the door open, though, the returning woman has reached her limit. When the woman flatmate opens the door, she is greeted by the sight of the returning woman assuming a peculiar posture and a facial expression of premature relief, as she is releasing the solid contents of her bowels into her pants (describe this in elaborate detail). Initially, the woman flatmate is befuddled as to why the returning woman has assumed such a posture and facial expression, and as to why the returning woman is frozen in place and not getting into the flat after the door has been finally opened for her. The woman flatmate asks the returning woman why she isn't entering, but is only met with soft grunts of exertion from the returning woman who is still in the midst of relieving herself in her pants. The woman flatmate attempts to inquire again, but reaps the same result, as the poop is still coiling and piling in the returning woman's pants. The returning woman then finishes relieving herself in her pants with a sigh of relief, while the woman flatmate is still gazing at her in confusion. As the woman flatmate is giving the returning woman a puzzled and bemused stare, she is met with the odor that is emanating from the deposit in the returning woman's pants, to which she reacts (describe this in elaborate detail). With bewilderment, the woman flatmate asks the returning woman if she just did what she thinks she did. The returning woman sheepishly replies that she's been holding a desperate urge to poop and misplaced her key, so she tried frantically calling and knocking to have the woman flatmate open the door for her, until it was too late. It is only after this exchange that the returning woman gingerly enters the flat, passing the woman flatmate as the latter is standing in front of the doorway and laughing. As the returning woman is entering and passing by the woman flatmate, the woman flatmate observes the bulge in the soiled pants of the returning woman, to which the woman flatmate reacts and comments on in a playfully teasing manner (describe this in elaborate detail). The returning woman is taking this playful teasing in stride and jokes along. The woman flatmate catches up to the returning woman after a few steps into the flat (as the playful teasing is still going on), gently stops the cooperating returning woman in her tracks, delicately turns her by the wrist so she can observe her rear end and further playfully comment on the state of the the returning woman's soiled pants (describe this in elaborate detail). The woman flatmate is replied to in a playful manner by the returning woman, who emphasizes how relieved she is after moving her bowels and how good it feels to let go after holding for such a long time - even if it came out in her pants. As she is observing the soiled pants, the woman flatmate is sniffing the air around the returning woman, and playfully reacts to the odor and teases the returning woman about it while doing so (describe this in elaborate detail). The returning woman is taking all of this in stride and partaking in the playful banter, all while reacting to her own odor as well. Finally, the woman flatmate relents as she's chuckling and lets the returning woman head to clean herself up.

Tell me more about Naomi's appearance. How was her predicament established and foreshadowed in previous scenes? Describe this in detail, and in a manner that is coherent and consistent with the predicament itself. Tell me more about Naomi's expression of relief and concentration. Tell me more about her posture. Tell me more about her soft grunts. Tell me more about the poop coiling and piling in her leggings. Tell me more about the bulging in her leggings. Tell me more about the smell emanating from her. Tell me more about Kimberly waving her hand in front of her nose. Tell me more about the two women's banter over the pungent smell in the air. Tell me more about Kimberly holding her nose. Tell me more about Naomi becoming free of her awkward stance and heading to the bathroom.

content:
We resisted the temptation to become overtly prescriptive in the preceding chapters, but early readers urged us to get specific with practical advice. So we did.

Learning Tips for Students

Embrace the fact that significant learning is often difficult, and that setbacks are signs of effort, not failure. Effortful learning changes your brain, building expertise and increasing your capability.

Practice Retrieving New Learning from Memory

When you read a text or study lecture notes, ask yourself questions like these, without looking in the text, to help you remember the key ideas.

Set aside a little time every week throughout the semester to quiz yourself on the material in a course.

Use quizzing to identify weak mastery areas and focus your studying to make them strong.

Most studiers focus on underlining and highlighting text and lecture notes and slides, but self-quizzing is far more potent for learning than additional rereading.

Rereading creates illusions of knowing, but quizzing yourself on the main ideas and the meanings behind the terms helps you focus on the central precepts and arrests forgetting. Quizzing strengthens your learning of new knowledge and skills and helps you recall it in the future.

Self-quizzing feels awkward and frustrating, but it strengthens your memory, and you learn more if you restudy something after failing to recall it.

Space Out Your Retrieval Practice

Spaced practice means studying information more than once but leaving considerable time between practice sessions. Establish a schedule of self-quizzing that allows time to elapse between study sessions, and quiz yourself on new material once a month.

If you use flashcards, keep quizzing yourself on the cards you answer correctly, and set them aside to revisit periodically. Interleave the study of two or more topics to ensure that you continually refresh your memory.

Intuition persuades us to dedicate stretches of time to single-minded, repetitive practice of something we want to master, but we fail to see how quickly the gains made during single-minded repetitive practice fade, leaving us with the impression that massed practice is productive.

If you space out your practice sessions and use self- quizzing as your primary study strategy, you will have to work harder to reconstruct what you already studied, which makes the important ideas more salient and memorable.

Massed practice feels more productive than spaced practice, but it is not. Spaced practice helps you to reconstruct learning from long-term memory.

Interleave the Study of Different Problem Types

Many textbooks are structured in study blocks that supply many examples to solve before moving on to another kind of problem. Interleaved practice is more effective.

Once you understand a problem type, scatter the problem type throughout your practice sequence so that you can quiz yourself on each.

A baseball player who practices batting by swinging at fastballs, curveballs, and changeups will perform better in practice than a player who mixes it up.

Most learners focus on many examples of one problem type at a time, but mixing up problem types and specimens improves your ability to discriminate between types, identify the unifying characteristics within a type, and apply the correct solution.

When you practice one type of problem before moving on to another type, it feels like you're getting better mastery, but this feeling is illusory.

Other Effective Study Strategies

Elaboration is the process of finding additional layers of meaning in new material. Examples include relating the material to what you already know and explaining it to somebody else.

When studying physics, you can better grasp the principles of angular momentum by visualizing a figure skater's rotation speeding up as her arms are drawn into her body. When studying heat transfer, you can better understand conduction by imagining warming your hands around a hot cup of cocoa.

Mary Pat Wenderoth encourages her students to elaborate by assigning them the task of creating large "summary sheets", which show graphically and through key words how the various biological systems interrelate with each other.

GENERATION is an attempt to answer a question or solve a problem before being shown the answer or the solution. It improves learning and memory of a text.

Many people perceive their learning to be most effective when it is experiential, and this is a form of generation. Bonnie Blodgett provides a strong example of generative learning in Chapter 4.

When reading new class material, you can practice generation by explaining beforehand the key ideas you expect to find and how they relate to your prior knowledge.

If you're in a science or math course, try to solve the problems before you get to class. The professors understand that it makes classroom learning stronger.

Reflection is the act of taking a few minutes to review what you have learned and asking yourself questions. It adds layers to learning and strengthens skills.

The biology professor Mary Pat Wenderoth assigns weekly low- stakes "learning paragraphs" in which students reflect on what they learned the previous week.

Calibration is the act of aligning your judgments of what you know and don't know with objective feedback so that you can avoid being carried off by the illusions of mastery.

Airline pilots use flight instruments to know when their perceptual systems are misleading them about critical factors like whether the airplane is fl ying level. Students use quizzes and practice tests to see whether they know as much as they think they do.

Mnemonic devices are tools for remembering things. They help you to retrieve what you have learned and to hold arbitrary information in memory, and they are used by psychology students at Bellerbys College in Oxford.

Michael Young, Medical Student

Young entered medical school without the usual foundation of premed coursework. He barely eked out a 65 on his fi rst exam, so he started reading empirical studies on learning and became deeply interested in the testing effect.

Young earned a master's degree in psychology, worked as a drug addiction counselor, and wondered if he would be happier in medicine. He cobbled together some courses from his local university, and took the Medical College Admission Test and managed to score well enough to get into medical school.

When he found himself very far indeed from being over the hump, he became more mindful of that when he studied, and went back and checked if he was way off base or on the right track. The retrieval practice was not a natural fi t for him, but he made himself stick to it long enough to see if it worked. It ended up working out really well for him.

Young spoke with us about how he adapted the principles of spaced retrieval practice to medical school.

When you go back and review, make sure you can recall the learning. If not, go back and look at it again.

On finding the right spacing for practice, the author says that the longer you wait to practice retrieval, the better it is for memory, but you have to be successful when you try to recall it.

Young has slowed down the speed at which he reads material, thinking about meaning and using elaboration to better understand it and lodge it in memory.

Young's impressive per for mance has not been lost on his professors or his peers, and he has been invited to tutor struggling students, an honor few are given.

Stephen Madigan, a professor at the University of Southern California, noticed Timothy Fellows was getting 90 to 95 percent on all his exams, papers, short- answer questions, multiple- choice questions. He asked Fellows about his study habits.

Madigan did not know Fellows outside of class, but he observed that he had a life beyond his academics. Fellows' study habits are still shared with incoming students.

The student always does the reading prior to a lecture, anticipates test questions, answers rhetorical questions in his head during lectures, reviews study guides, relearns terms, and copies bolded terms into a reading notebook.

Tips for Lifelong Learners

The strategies for learning we have just outlined are effective for anyone at any age, and are centered around classroom instruction. Lifelong learners use the same principles in a variety of less-structured settings.

Retrieval Practice

Nathaniel Fuller, a professional actor with the Guthrie Theater in Minneapolis, highlights all of his lines in a binder before starting to learn a new script. This makes it easy to find the lines and gives him a sense of the construction of the lines.

Fuller uses retrieval practice in various forms, including covering a page of the script and silently rendering the lines of the characters he's playing opposite. He checks his accuracy and goes on.

Half of knowing your part is knowing when to say it, and trying your best to remember it without looking at it.

"I work like crazy, and then quit when it feels like diminishing returns. Then I come back the next day and won't remember it."

As he progresses through the script, he practices from familiar pages and scenes into newer material, stitching less familiar material to more familiar, deepening his mastery of the role as a whole.

Fuller learns lines by examining the language of the script, the textures of the words, and the fi gures of speech for how they reveal meaning. This helps him develop an emotional approach to the role.

Fuller now speaks every line of the other actors into a palm-sized digital recorder, and uses his thumb to control the recorder. He speaks his lines from memory, checking the script as he goes.

Fuller practices at home, imagining his living room as the stage, and observes the actors in rehearsal, adapting the imaginary stage within his living room to the now-established blocking.

Fuller's learning process is a seamless blend of desirable difficulties that make his characters come alive to himself and his audience.

Generation

John McPhee, age eighty-two at the time, published a piece in the New Yorker about writer's block. In the piece, he tells his mother how miserable he feels, how he wants to write about a bear, but has no idea how to go about it.

McPhee's fi rst draft is an "awful blurting", but he keeps working on it while driving home, and he thinks of better ways to say something, a good phrase to correct a certain problem.

Learning works the same way as McPhee's "awful blurting": you have to engage the mind in trying to make sense of something new, by connecting the facts, making it vivid, relating it to what you already know.

Refl ection

In chapter 2 we tell how the Mayo Clinic neurosurgeon Mike Ebersold uses the habit of refl ection to improve his skills in the operating room. He devised a surgical solution for repairing a delicate sinus structure.

The power of refl ection as a learning technique is evident throughout the personal memoir Highest Duty, by Captain Chesley Sullenberger. Sullenberger used refl ection to improve his understanding of flight and the control of his aircraft through training, personal experience, and the close observation of others.

Elaboration

Thelma Hunter, who is eighty-eight, was learning four new works for an upcoming concert performance. She is not a prodigy or particularly renowned, but she is accomplished.

Hunter's methods include learning a new score physically, aurally, visually, and intellectually.

Hunter has made concessions to age, such as warming up before playing and thinking about the piece while driving. She visualizes the score and makes mental marginalia, and sometimes says it out loud, "Up an octave, at this point."

Hunter describes experiences that would seem to manifest Ericsson's theory that experts build libraries of mental models through thousands of hours of solo, deliberate practice. After having been away from the piece for a week, she will sit down and play it through using a fi ngering pattern that feels entirely natural.

Tips for Teachers

Here are some basic strategies that will help students become stronger learners in the classroom. We hope you will find practical ideas you can adapt and put to work.

Explain to Students How Learning Works

Students must be helped to understand the fundamental ideas about how people learn, so they can better manage their own education.

When learning is easy, it is often superfi cial and soon forgotten. When learning is effortful, the brain changes, making new connections and increasing intellectual ability.

Create Desirable Diffi culties in the Classroom

When practical, use frequent quizzing to help students consolidate learning and interrupt the pro cess of forgetting. Make the ground rules acceptable to your students and yourself.

Create study tools that incorporate retrieval practice, generation, and elaboration. These might include practice tests, writing exercises, and short statements that summarize recent material covered in a text or lecture.

Design quizzing and exercises to reach back to concepts and learning covered earlier in the term, to strengthen conceptual learning and develop deeper understanding of relationships between ideas.

Be Transparent

Help your students understand the difficulties you have incorporated into your lessons, and why it's worth persisting.

University of Washington

Mary Pat Wenderoth helps students master their coursework by introducing desirable difficulties, helping them be effective at managing their own learning, and helping them rise to the levels of synthesis and evaluation.

Bloom's taxonomy classifies cognitive learning on six levels, from gaining knowledge to analyzing ideas and making inferences, and from synthesising knowledge and ideas to evaluating opinions and making judgments based on evidence and objective criteria.

Wenderoth teaches her students about the testing effect, the principle of desirable difficulties, and the perils of "illusions of knowing" and promises to make her instructional philosophy transparent.

Wenderoth poses questions to the class, and they vote on which answer they think is correct. They then talk to people with different answers to figure out who has the correct answer.

Wenderoth gives her students a new way to think about learning, and a new vocabulary for describing setbacks. When students blame the test, it's not a good meeting ground for solving problems.

Wenderoth has transformed class "study groups" into "testing groups", where everyone wrestles with a question together, without opening the textbook.

Wenderoth will ask students what ideas they don't feel really clear on, then send one student to the whiteboard to try to explain the concept.

Wenderoth assigns her students to sit with a blank piece of paper and write everything they can remember from class for ten minutes. They are then to go to their class notes and focus on the material they forgot.

Wenderoth's students create summary sheets every Monday, which are large cartoons dense with callouts, blowups, directional arrows, and the like. The sheets help them synthesize a week's information, thinking through how systems are connected.

Wenderoth will assign students to write low-stakes "learning paragraphs" on a Friday if she doesn't feel she's overburdening them, to stimulate retrieval and reflection, and to capture a week's learning before it is lost to the countless other concerns and diversions of college life.

Wenderoth has translated her class material into the different levels of Bloom's taxonomy of learning, and has students identify where their answers fell on the taxonomy and think about what they need to know to respond at a higher level.

Poorly prepared students seldom survive entry-level science courses, and as a result, even students whose interests and aptitudes might lead them to successful science careers never get through the door.

Wenderoth and her colleagues have found that high-structure classes reduce student failure rates and increase exam results compared to low-structure classes. The high-structure classes also teach students the importance of having a "growth mindset" (that learning is hard work and that struggle increases intellectual abilities).

Wenderoth says he teaches students to think like professionals and show them how to get up again when they fall.

Michael D. Matthews, Psychology Professor, U.S. Military Academy at West Point

The pedagogical philosophy at West Point is founded on the Thayer method, which incorporates quizzing and recitation in every class meeting.

Students at West Point must focus on three pillars of training: academic, military, and physical. They must learn to zero in on what's essential and let the rest fall by the wayside.

Matthews's courses focus on constructs, not specifi c facts, and include daily quizzing and active problem solving with feedback. Students "take to the boards" to collaborate on answering higher-order questions, and one student is selected from each group to give a recitation to the class explaining how the group has answered the question.

West Point teaches you how to shoot an azimuth, a skill used for keeping your bearings in unfamiliar territory. Quizzing is a way of shooting an azimuth in the classroom.

Cadet Kiley Hunkler won a Rhodes Scholarship and will be attending Oxford University and Johns Hopkins Medical School. She created learning objectives for each major course block and took a practice test every three days to see how she was doing.

One of this book's authors attended Riverside Military Academy in Gainesville, Georgia, and found that the Thayer method worked well for students who were not prone to work hard on their own outside of class.

Kathleen McDermott, Psychology Professor, Washington University at St. Louis

Kathleen McDermott gives daily low- stakes quizzes in a university course on human learning and memory. The questions hit the high points of the lecture, the readings, or both, and students have to think in order to do well.

McDermott sets the ground rules very clearly at the start of the term and explains why the quizzes are helpful, even if they don't feel helpful. Students initially are not happy about the quiz regime, but by the end of the semester they say that the quizzes have helped them keep up with the course.

McDermott gives two midterm exams and a final, and uses quizzes to reinforce learning. He also gives cumulative exams, which reinforce learning by requiring students to engage in spaced review.

Columbia, Illinois, Public School District

We have worked with teachers in a middle school in Columbia, Illinois to test the effects of integrating low- stakes quizzing into the curriculum. The project has since been extended to high school history and science classes.

The Illinois State Board of Education has adopted new math and English language arts standards for K - 12 education in line with the Common Core State Standards Initiative. The Columbia School District is redesigning its curriculum and its tests to be more rigorous and to engage students in more writing and analysis work.

In- Service Training

Licensed professionals in many fields must earn continuing education credits to keep their skills current and maintain their licenses. If you see yourself in this scenario, you might consider using the presentation materials to quiz yourself on the key ideas and scheduling follow-up emails to appear in your inbox every month or so.

A new commercial training platform called Qstream sends learners periodic quizzes via their mobile devices to strengthen learning through spaced retrieval practice. A similar platform called Osmosis uses crowdsourced practice questions and explanations.

Kathy Maixner, Business Coach

The Maixner Group, based in Portland, Oregon, helps companies grow by improving their sales tactics. One big company added $21 million to its annual revenue after hooking up with Maixner.

Maixner's coaching techniques line up with the learning principles described in this book. She helps clients discover the root causes of a problem, generate possible solutions, and play out the implications of different strategies before committing to one.

Maixner's experience working with clients in many different fields helps her see around corners, where the hazards lie, and introduces the difficulties that make the learning stronger.

Farmers Insurance

Corporate sales training can be complicated, but Farmers Insurance's new-agent training is an excellent example of interleaving the learning and practice of different but related topics so that each adds meaning to the other.

The company recruits upward of two thousand new agents annually, and they attend an intensive weeklong program of learning exercises.

Participants are given magazines, scissors, and marking pens to illustrate what being a successful Farmers agent would look like to them personally, five years down the road. The point is simple: work backward to set the metrics for where you need to be.

The learning unfolds through a series of exercises that require participants to recall what they have learned earlier.

When participants first arrive, they're assigned to a red, blue, or green group. The green group is instructed to ask others about their family, prior occupation, favorite forms of recreation, and what they enjoy most.

When talking about sales, a good way to learn about a prospective customer is to ask about their family, occupation, recreation, and enjoyment.

Throughout the week, four principal training topics are repeatedly touched on, a point is made, and the exercises shift to related questions. Participants brainstorm how to generate five hundred new policies in a year through marketing and development.

Practice is a central learning strategy for sales agents. They practice how to respond to a sales lead and also learn about the products they're selling.

Given the limited resources new agents have to invest, how do agents determine which strategies will pay off? Most agents guess that a direct mail campaign will return 1 percent.

The Farmers Insurance acronym FORE helps agents discover needs that a lead has that the company's products can meet. Through generation, spaced practice, and interleaving of the essential core curriculum, new agents learn what they need to do, and how.

Jiffy Lube University, an integrated suite of educational courses under the felicitous name Jiffy Lube University, is helping the company's franchisees win customers, reduce employee turnover, broaden their ser vice offerings, and boost sales.

The rapid- oil- change business has had to adjust to changes in the marketplace and advances in technology.

Jiffy Lube University is a Web-based learning platform that certifies technicians as proficient. After scoring 80 percent or better on an exam, employees begin training on the job, practicing new skills by following a written guide that breaks each service activity into its component steps.

Jiffy Lube's e-learning and on-the-job training incorporate quizzing, feedback, and spaced and interleaved practice to provide an individualized learning plan and monitor progress against the company's completion schedule.

Ken Barber, manager of learning and development at Jiffy Lube International, is putting the finishing touches on a computer-based simulation game for company managers called "A Day in the Life of a Store Manager".

Jiffy Lube University has received many accolades from the training profession and earned accreditation by the American Council on Education. Employee turnover has dropped and customer satisfaction has increased since the program's beginning.

Andersen Windows and Doors

At Andersen Windows and Doors, a culture of continuous improvement turns learning on its head, with production workers teaching the managers how to make the plant more efficient.

The company's division called Renewal by Andersen produces replacement windows of all types and sizes. The production line is divided into three work cells, each with four work stations, and workers change jobs every two hours to minimize repetitive stress injuries and broaden cross-training.

Every job is performed to a written standard, and every new employee is trained following an instructional sequence of practice and feedback that Wynveen calls "tell - show - do - review".

Workers train the managers when they have an idea for improving productivity, and when a production line team doesn't meet its targets, the workers are asked to identify the problem and redesign the production process to solve it.

Wynveen recruited a team to engage in a Kaizen event to increase the productivity of the plant's double-hung window line by 40 percent and doubling production. The team met in a conference room eight hours a day for a week.

Wynveen asked production workers what changes were needed to make their plan work, and then the line was disassembled and rebuilt in two halves, over two weekends, restarted, and fine-tuned over subsequent months. The result was that the plant met its stretch goals and cut costs in half.

A learning culture empowers employees to change the system and solve problems, and makes learning an engine for continuous improvement.

Inner Gate Acu punc ture

Erik Isaacman, a thirty-something husband, father of two, and passionate practitioner of traditional Chinese medicine, had a clinic that was succeeding in its therapeutic mission but struggling as a business.

Erik and Oliver Leonetti opened Inner Gate in 2005, and the business grew quickly. But they didn't have the systems in place to manage costs, and they didn't have clear goals or a management hierarchy.

Erik and Oliver's business coach Kathy Maixner helped them create the infrastructure they needed to grow their business: an operating manual, job descriptions, financial goals, metrics for measuring the performance of their clinicians.

Maixner used generation, reflection, elaboration, and rehearsal in her coaching sessions to help her partners become effective managers who delegate and empower their employees.

Erik's becoming an effective coach and teacher of his coworkers has helped put the clinic on sound footing. The new protocol helps clinicians clarify what brought the patient in and recommend a treatment plan.

We role-play as patient and clinician, raise questions, objections, and practice responding to the patient and the clinic. Then we listen to the differences.

Erik and Oliver have built a top-rated acupuncture clinic in Portland by dedicating themselves to being learners as well as teachers.

The techniques for highly effective learning outlined in this book can be put to use right now everywhere learners, teachers, and trainers are at work. They come at no cost, require no structural reform, and promise both real and long-lasting benefits.

(In the clubroom…)

Monika: “Wait a minute…where’s Natsuki?”

Yuri: “I honestly don’t know.”

Sayori: “I’ll give her a call, just in case.”

(Sayori takes out her phone and dials Natsuki’s number. After a few rings, Natsuki finally answers.)

Natsuki: “Hello?”

Sayori: “Natsuki! Where are you? We were getting worried.”

Natsuki: “Oh, sorry for not letting you guys know. I went to the bakery near my house to pick up some pastries for us.”

Sayori: “That’s where you disappeared to? Well, hurry back! We miss you.”

Natsuki: “I’m on my way. Don’t start the club activities without me!”

(Sayori hangs up the call and turns to the others.)

Sayori: “She’s just at the bakery. She’ll be here soon.”

Monika: “Good. It’s not the same without her.”

Yuri: “Indeed. Natsuki definitely adds a unique energy to our club.”

(As they wait for Natsuki to return, they discuss the upcoming literature festival and potential ideas for their club presentation.)

Monika: “So, how about we focus on exploring different forms of poetry? It would be an excellent opportunity to showcase our individual styles.”

Yuri: “I agree. We can highlight the diversity and versatility of poetry as an art form.”

Sayori: “That sounds great! We can also include some of our favorite poems to share with everyone.”

(The conversation continues, with each member contributing their ideas and suggestions. Just as they finish discussing, Natsuki bursts through the clubroom door, holding a box of pastries.)

Natsuki: “I’m back, and I brought snacks!”

Monika: “Welcome back, Natsuki! We were just discussing our ideas for the literature festival.”

Natsuki: “Well, I hope you saved the best for last because I brought some delicious pastries!”

(Natsuki places the box of pastries on the table, and the enticing aroma fills the room.)

Yuri: “Wow, they look amazing, Natsuki. Thank you for thinking of us.”

Sayori: “I can already tell these will be the highlight of our club activities today!”

Natsuki: “You better believe it! Now, let’s dig in and enjoy these tasty treats while we finalize our plans.”

(The club members eagerly grab a pastry of their choice and find their seats. As they savor the sweet delicacies, the lively club atmosphere returns.)

Monika: “Alright, now that we’re all here, let’s go through our ideas one more time.”

Yuri: “Agreed. It’s important to make sure our presentation captures the essence of our club and leaves a lasting impression.”

(Sayori and Natsuki nod in agreement as they munch on their pastries.)

Sayori: “I think we should also incorporate some interactive elements into our presentation. It’ll keep the audience engaged and interested.”

Natsuki: “Yeah, we could even challenge them to create their own short poems. It’ll be fun to see their creativity!”

Monika: “Great suggestion, Natsuki. That’ll definitely make our presentation memorable.”

(As they discuss and fine-tune their ideas, the club members enjoy their pastries and bond over their shared enthusiasm for literature. With each passing moment, their excitement for the literature festival grows stronger.)

(After the club meeting, Monika heads towards Natsuki’s house. She finds Natsuki inside a kids room - one that was completely empty, apart from some furniture like a basinet and a bed - a sad expression on her face, as if she wanted the room to be for any children she wanted to have.)

Monika: “Hey, Natsuki. Are you okay?”

(Natsuki looks up, her eyes filled with sadness.)

Natsuki: “Oh, Monika. I didn’t expect to see you here.”

Monika: “I noticed you seemed a bit down earlier, so I wanted to check up on you. Is everything alright?”

Natsuki: “It’s just…this room. It was supposed to be for…well, for my future children. But…no matter how many pregnancy tests I take…”

Monika: “Oh, Natsuki, I’m so sorry. I had no idea you were going through this.”

Natsuki: “It’s alright, Monika. I just…I don’t understand why it’s not happening for me. It feels like everyone else can have kids so easily, and here I am, struggling.”

Monika: “I can’t even begin to imagine how difficult this must be for you. But please remember, you’re not alone in this. We’re all here for you, and we support you.”

Natsuki: “Thank you, Monika. It means a lot to me. It’s just hard sometimes, seeing all my hopes and dreams for a family slipping away.”

Monika: “I understand. But please don’t give up hope. Sometimes things don’t happen according to our plans, but that doesn’t mean they can’t happen at all. And even if having children may not be in your future, there are other ways to build a fulfilling and happy life.”

Natsuki: “You’re right, Monika. I shouldn’t let this define me. There’s more to life than just having children.”

Monika: “Exactly. You have so much to offer, Natsuki. Your passion for baking, your creativity, your kind heart - those are the qualities that make you special. And I truly believe that you can find happiness, no matter what the future holds.”

Natsuki: “Thank you, Monika. I really needed to hear that. It’s just hard to see beyond the disappointment and frustration sometimes.” (getting an idea) “Hang on…you know how to code, right, Monika?”

Monika: “Yes, I do. Why do you ask?”

Natsuki: “Well, maybe you could use that coding skill of yours to actually *make* me pregnant?”

(As I walked to the clubroom, I couldn’t believe what happened yesterday. MC, my childhood friend, had died. The news hit me like a ton of bricks. And as I entered the clubroom, I could see Monika and Himari discussing something. Kotonhoa was also there, and was moving a strange pool - it was round and pink. Yuri was there, too - she was filling the pool with warm water. I was confused as to what they were doing, but was even more confused as to where Natsuki was.)

Yuri: “And…that should be everything!”

Monika: “Great job, Yuri. I’ll set up the decorations now.”

Himari: “I’m so excited for this pool party! It’s going to be so much fun!”

Kotonoha: “I hope everyone likes my special punch!”

(I cleared my throat to let them know I was there.)

Sayori: (trying to keep my voice steady) “Hey guys.”

(They all turned to look at me with sad expressions.)

Monika: “Sayori, how are you holding up?”

Sayori: “I’m…not doing well. MC’s death is still a really hard pill to swallow.”

Yuri: “We understand, Sayori. We’re all grieving. But we thought it might be good to distract ourselves with a pool party.”

Himari: “Yeah! We’ll have food, drinks, music, and swimming! It’ll be a blast!”

Kotonoha: “And don’t forget my special punch! It’s delicious!”

Sayori: (forcing a smile) “That sounds like a lot of fun. But…I’m not sure I’m in the mood to party.”

Monika: “We understand, Sayori. But please, try to have some fun. It’s what MC would have wanted.”

Sayori: (nodding slowly) “Yeah…you’re right. MC was always the life of the party. He wouldn’t want us moping around.”

Himari: “That’s the spirit! Now, let’s get this party started!”

Yuri: “Hold on. Does anybody else notice a lack of somebody?”

Kotonoha: “You’re right, Yuri. Where’s Natsuki?”

Monika: “I haven’t seen her all day. Has anyone tried contacting her?”

Sayori: “I texted her earlier, but she hasn’t replied.”

Himari: “I hope she’s okay.”

(Just then, Natsuki burst into the room - and immediately got into the pool, putting a hand on her massive belly. I was thoroughly confused as to why.)

Natsuki: (panting) “Sorry guys, I’m late. I just had to take care of something important.”

Monika: “Natsuki, are you okay? You look exhausted.”

Natsuki: “I’m fine. Just a little tired.”

Yuri: “And why are you in the pool already?”

Natsuki: (looking down at her belly) “Oh this? I just wanted to cool off. It’s been really hot today.”

Kotonoha: “Natsuki, are you sure you’re okay? You seem a bit…different.”

Natsuki: (smiling) “I’m fine, Kotonoha. Just a little pregnant, that’s all.”

Himari: (gasping) “Pregnant? Natsuki, that’s amazing!”

Sayori: “Congratulations, Natsuki! That’s wonderful news!”

Monika: “We’re so happy for you!”

Yuri: “Yes, congratulations.”

Kotonoha: “I can’t wait to make some special punch for the baby shower!”

Natsuki: (in severe pain) “I-I-It’s a little too late for a baby shower, Kotonhoa.”

(We all looked at Natsuki, confused.)

Himari: “What do you mean, Natsuki? Are you not well?”

Natsuki: (gritting her teeth) “I’m in labor, you guys.”

Monika: (shocked) “Labor?! Oh my God, we need to get you to the hospital!”

Natsuki: “The contractions are too close together, Monika. I need to give birth right here, in the clubroom!”

(The rest of us sprang into action, trying to make the clubroom as comfortable as possible for Natsuki. Yuri brought towels and a pillow, while Kotonoha helped her to the ground.)

Sayori: “What do we do? None of us have any experience delivering a baby.”

Monika: “Maybe I should try and call an ambulance?”

Natsuki: (shaking her head) “No time for that. I need you guys to help me deliver this baby.”

Himari: “We’ll do anything we can to help, Natsuki.”

Yuri: “I read about childbirth once…maybe I can assist in some way.”

Monika: “I’ll try and keep you calm, Natsuki.”

Kotonoha: “I’ll get some water and snacks ready in case you need it.”

(Suddenly, Natsuki let out a loud scream, causing all of us to jump.)

Natsuki: (breathing heavily) “Okay, it’s time. Yuri, I need you to grab a clean towel and some warm water.”

(Yuri quickly followed Natsuki’s instructions, while the rest of us watched in awe.)

Sayori: “This is incredible.”

Monika: “It’s nerve-wracking, too.”

Himari: “But it’s also a miracle.”

Kotonoha: “I can’t believe we’re about to witness the miracle of life.”

(As the labor progressed, we all took turns assisting Natsuki - holding her hand, wiping her forehead, and encouraging her. And finally, after what felt like an eternity, a tiny baby emerged.)

Natsuki: (overjoyed) “He’s here! My little boy is finally here!”

(The rest of us were in tears at the sight of the beautiful, brand new life.)

Monika: “Congratulations, Natsuki. You did amazing.”

Himari: “He’s so cute and tiny.”

Kotonoha: “What’s his name?”

Natsuki: (smiling) “His name is MC.”

(Everyone looked at Natsuki with surprised expressions.)

Yuri: “MC…after our childhood friend?”

Natsuki: “Yes. I couldn’t think of a better name for my little boy than after my dear friend who I lost. I hope he grows up to be just like him.”

Sayori: “That’s so sweet, Natsuki.”

(We all took turns holding and cooing over baby MC, feeling grateful to have witnessed such a beautiful moment. And as we packed up the pool party decorations, we all knew that this day would be one that we would never forget. 7 years later, I went to see Natsuki and little MC - even though I was 5 months pregnant with triplets.)

(In the clubroom…)

Monika: “Wait a minute…where’s Natsuki?”

Yuri: “I have no idea. Can’t think straight with this baby bump.” (rubbing her belly) “My sweet little Violet’s also not very active as usual. She’s making me worried…”

Sayori: “I’ll give her a call, just in case.”

(Sayori takes out her phone and dials Natsuki’s number. After a few rings, Natsuki answers.)

Natsuki: “Hello?”

Sayori: “Hey, Natsuki! We realized you’re not here in the clubroom. Is everything alright?”

Natsuki: “Oh, hey Sayori. Yeah, everything’s fine. I just had some stuff to take care of. I didn’t want to bother you guys since you all seemed busy.”

Yuri: “Are you sure you’re alright, Natsuki? We were a bit worried when we didn’t see you.”

Natsuki: “Yeah, yeah, I’m really okay. No need to worry, guys. I’ll be there in a bit, alright?”

Monika: “Alright, just make sure you’re alright, Natsuki. We care about you, you know.”

Natsuki: “Thanks, Monika. I appreciate it. See you soon, guys.”

(They all hang up and wait for Natsuki to arrive.)

Yuri: “I hope she’s telling the truth and everything is okay.”

Monika: “Let’s give her the benefit of the doubt. We’ll find out soon.”

(Soon enough, Natsuki arrives in the clubroom, slightly out of breath.)

Sayori: “Natsuki, you’re finally here! Is everything alright?”

Natsuki: “Yeah, sorry for the worry. I just had a little situation to deal with, but it’s all sorted now. Thanks for checking up on me.”

Yuri: “We care about you, Natsuki. If anything’s ever bothering you, don’t hesitate to let us know.”

Natsuki: “I know, Yuri. I appreciate it.”

Monika: “Well, now that everyone’s here, let’s get back to our activities. Natsuki, did you bring some manga to share?”

Natsuki: “Of course! I wouldn’t miss it.”

Yuri: (clutching her baby bump) “…oh, gosh…oh, gosh…”

Sayori: “Yuri, are you okay? What’s wrong?”

Yuri: “I…I think Violet is…coming sooner than expected. I’m having contractions. Oh, gosh, this hurts so much…”

Monika: “Yuri, don’t worry! We’ll take care of you. Sayori, call an ambulance right away!”

(Sayori quickly dials for an ambulance while Monika and Natsuki help Yuri to a nearby couch.)

Natsuki: “Hang in there, Yuri. We’ll be with you every step of the way.”

Monika: “Yuri, try to stay calm. Just breathe and focus on getting through the contractions. The ambulance is on its way.”

(Yuri nods, tightly gripping Monika’s hand as the contractions continue.)

Sayori: (on the phone) “Yes, hello? We have an emergency. Our friend is in labor and experiencing painful contractions. We need an ambula-”

Yuri: (noticing a small puddle of water that had formed between her legs) “Uh…guys?”

Monika: “Yuri, what is it?”

Yuri: “I think my water just broke…I’m fully dilated…”

(In the clubroom…)

Monika: “Wait a minute…where’s Natsuki?”

Sayori: “I honestly don’t know.”

Yuri: “No idea.” (rubbing her 7-month baby bump) “Can’t really think straight with this belly…and Violet’s lack of movement just isn’t helping.”

Monika: “Hmm, that’s strange. She’s usually here before all of us. Maybe she got caught up with something?”

Sayori: “Maybe we should try giving her a call? Just to make sure everything’s alright.”

Yuri: “That’s a good idea. I hope she’s okay.”

(They call Natsuki, but there’s no answer.)

Monika: “No luck, huh? Well, maybe she’ll show up soon. In the meantime, let’s start our meeting.”

(As they begin discussing club activities, there’s a knock on the door.)

Natsuki: (panting) “Sorry, sorry! I’m here.”

Sayori: “Natsuki, where were you? We were starting to get worried!”

Natsuki: “I got caught up with something at home, lost track of time. Sorry for making you all wait.”

Yuri: “Is everything okay? You seem a bit flustered.”

Natsuki: “Yeah, I’m fine. Just some…family stuff going on. Nothing to worry about.”

Monika: “Alright, if you say so. We’re just glad you’re here now.”

(Yuri’s stomach ripples slightly.)

Yuri: “Oh! Looks like Violet’s finally awake! Want to feel her kicking, Natsuki?”

Hello, can you write an alternate ending for the Foster’s Home For Imaginary Friends episode “Go Goo Go” where Mac meets a girl named Goo who begins to follow him to Foster’s every day. Her over-active imagination creates many new imaginary friends, which causes Foster’s to become overcrowded, which goes the same after Mac yells at her, and apologizes as Goo hugs him tightly only Mac is moved by the embrace and develops a crush on Goo, but denies it, and does his best to hide it, and the effects on the proceeding episodes where Goo appears such as
”The Big Picture” - Everyone prepares for the annual house photo; Bloo, Mac and Goo try to solve the mystery of a strange photo of Foster’s
”Neighbor Pains” - It is Adopt-A-Thought Saturday, and Goo helps out with her organizational skills
”Infernal Slumber” - Bloo, Wilt, Eduardo, Goo and Coco join Mac at his home for a surprise slumber party on a school night, however, Mac struggles to keep them quiet and not wake his mom
”I Only Have Surprise for You” - Mac tries everything that he possibly can to prevent Bloo and the gang from throwing him a surprise party
”Bus the Two of Us” - Bloo decides to take Mac for a ride on the Foster Mansion bus but meanwhile, Wilt has to stop Frankie and Mr Rabbit from finding out that the bus isn’t in the garage, Goo helps in the distraction by creating imaginary versions of Mac and Bloo
”The Big Cheese” - The residents at Foster’ s must get ready for a news show, but Cheese keeps testing everyone’s patience at the same time Mr Herriman places a new alarm system to keep Cheese out, but messes up the code and when everyone gets locked out, the only one who knows the code is Cheese, Goo helps out in getting the code from Cheese
”Make Believe It or Not” - During a power outage, Goo creates an imaginary game at home but when she dreams of the villain characters from the game and accidentally brings them all into real life, they imprison Mac and Bloo at home
”Schlock Star” - Some imaginary friends form a band and won’t let Bloo join, and he becomes determined to beat them at their own game and creates his own rock band and they hold a concert, which Goo acts as MC
”Goodbye to Bloo” - Bloo and the Friends think Mac is moving away forever, so they set out to make his last day at Foster’s the greatest he’s ever had, Goo appears and sings a nonsensical song to Mac, she remains oblivious to the celebration, but in the end it was a misunderstanding; Mac and his family are just moving to another apartment within the complex they already live in rather than moving to a whole new city as Mac elaborates on this by explaining that his mom got a promotion at work and needs a home office, so the family needs to move into a bigger place
But throughout all them, Goo knew all along and was just waiting for him to be honest and have the courage to confess? How do these scenarios play out?
Thanks
